var tafsirData_3 = {
  1: {
    "Alif-Lãm-Mĩm": "These are mysterious letters that appear at the beginning of some chapters of the Quran. They are known as 'Huruf al-Muqatta'at' (disjointed letters). Their exact meaning is known only to Allah. Some scholars say they serve to capture attention before a great message, while others say they demonstrate the miraculous nature of the Quran—that although it is composed of the same Arabic letters people use daily, no one can produce anything like it. This humbles human intellect and reminds us that Allah's knowledge is beyond our full comprehension."
  },
  2: {
    "Allah!": "This is the greatest name of God, the proper name of the Creator that encompasses all His perfect attributes. It is a declaration that demands attention and reverence.",
    "There is no god worthy of worship except Him": "This is the core message of Islam—Tawheed (monotheism). It means that no deity, idol, person, or creation deserves worship except Allah alone. Everything else that people worship is false. This statement negates all false gods and affirms the sole right of Allah to be worshipped.",
    "the Ever-Living": "Allah is Al-Hayy—the One who possesses perfect, eternal life. Unlike created beings who are born and die, Allah's life has no beginning and no end. He never sleeps, grows tired, or diminishes in any way.",
    "All-Sustaining": "Allah is Al-Qayyum—the Self-Subsisting One who sustains and maintains all of creation. Every creature depends on Him for its existence, while He depends on nothing and no one. As mentioned in Ayat al-Kursi (2:255), 'Neither drowsiness overtakes Him nor sleep.'"
  },
  3: {
    "He has revealed to you ˹O Prophet˺ the Book in truth": "Allah has sent down the Quran to Prophet Muhammad ﷺ, and this Book is filled with truth—there is no falsehood, no contradiction, and no error in it. It is the absolute truth from the Lord of all worlds, containing true stories, true guidance, and true laws.",
    "confirming what came before it": "The Quran does not contradict the original messages of previous scriptures; rather, it confirms the core truths they contained—especially the message of monotheism and righteous living. This shows the continuity of Allah's guidance throughout history.",
    "as He revealed the Torah and the Gospel": "Just as Allah revealed the Quran, He also revealed the Torah to Prophet Musa (Moses) and the Gospel (Injeel) to Prophet Isa (Jesus). All these scriptures came from the same source—Allah—and carried the same essential message of worshipping Him alone."
  },
  4: {
    "previously, as a guide for people": "The Torah and Gospel were sent before the Quran as guidance for humanity—to show them the right path, to teach them about their Creator, and to instruct them in righteous living. Every scripture Allah sent was meant to guide people to salvation.",
    "and ˹also˺ revealed the Standard ˹to distinguish between right and wrong˺": "Allah also revealed the Furqan—the Criterion. This refers to the ability granted through divine revelation to distinguish clearly between truth and falsehood, right and wrong, guidance and misguidance. The Quran itself is the ultimate Furqan, as it clarifies all matters of faith and life.",
    "Surely those who reject Allah's revelations will suffer a severe torment": "Those who knowingly deny, mock, or turn away from Allah's clear signs and scriptures will face a painful punishment. This is a serious warning to those who hear the truth but choose to reject it out of arrogance or desire.",
    "For Allah is Almighty, capable of punishment": "Allah is Al-Aziz—the All-Mighty who cannot be overpowered or resisted. His power is absolute. And He is fully capable of taking retribution from those who disobey Him. No one can escape His judgment."
  },
  5: {
    "Surely nothing on earth or in the heavens is hidden from Allah": "Allah's knowledge is perfect and all-encompassing. Nothing escapes His awareness—not the smallest atom, not the deepest secret in someone's heart, not anything in the darkest depths of the ocean or the farthest reaches of the universe. As Allah says elsewhere, 'He knows what is in the land and the sea. Not a leaf falls but that He knows it' (6:59). This should make believers conscious of their actions and give them comfort that Allah sees their struggles and rewards their efforts."
  },
  6: {
    "He is the One Who shapes you in the wombs of your mothers as He wills": "Allah is the Master Designer who forms every human being in the womb. He determines your appearance, your gender, your abilities, and your unique characteristics according to His perfect will and wisdom. No two people are exactly alike—each person is a unique creation. This shows Allah's incredible power and creativity. Modern science confirms the amazing complexity of fetal development, yet Allah accomplishes it with perfect ease.",
    "There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him": "This fundamental truth is repeated to emphasize that the One who creates you from nothing, shapes you with such precision, and gives you life—He alone deserves your worship. How can anyone worship something that cannot even create a fly?",
    "the Almighty, All-Wise": "Allah combines absolute power (Al-Aziz) with perfect wisdom (Al-Hakeem). His might is not arbitrary; everything He does is based on infinite wisdom. He places everything in its right place at the right time for the right purpose."
  },
  7: {
    "He is the One Who has revealed to you ˹O Prophet˺ the Book": "Allah directly revealed the Quran to Prophet Muhammad ﷺ through the angel Jibreel (Gabriel). This emphasizes the divine origin of the Quran—it is not the words of any human but the actual speech of Allah.",
    "of which some verses are precise—they are the foundation of the Book": "The precise verses (Muhkamat) are clear, unambiguous, and easily understood. They form the foundation and core of the Quran's message. These include verses about Allah's oneness, basic laws, moral principles, and clear commands and prohibitions. When studying the Quran, these clear verses should be the lens through which we understand everything else.",
    "while others are elusive": "The elusive verses (Mutashabihat) are those that may have multiple possible meanings or whose full reality is known only to Allah—such as descriptions of the unseen world, certain attributes of Allah, or the mysterious letters at the beginning of some chapters. These verses require careful study and should be understood in light of the clear verses.",
    "Those with deviant hearts follow the elusive verses seeking ˹to spread˺ doubt through their ˹false˺ interpretations": "People with spiritual diseases in their hearts—arrogance, desire to mislead others, or love of controversy—deliberately focus on the unclear verses. They twist their meanings to create confusion, spread doubts, and justify their false beliefs. This is a dangerous approach that leads people astray.",
    "but none grasps their ˹full˺ meaning except Allah": "The complete and ultimate meaning of certain verses is known only to Allah. Human beings, no matter how knowledgeable, have limitations. This teaches humility—we accept that we cannot know everything.",
    "As for those well-grounded in knowledge, they say, \"We believe in this ˹Quran˺—it is all from our Lord.\"": "The truly knowledgeable scholars approach the Quran with faith and humility. They believe in all of it—both the clear and the unclear—because they trust that it all comes from their Lord. They do not reject what they do not fully understand; rather, they accept it with faith.",
    "But none will be mindful ˹of this˺ except people of reason": "Only those who use their intellect properly—combining knowledge with faith, and reason with humility—will truly understand and benefit from this guidance. True intelligence leads to submission to Allah, not arrogance."
  },
  8: {
    "˹They say,˺ \"Our Lord! Do not let our hearts deviate after you have guided us.\"": "This is a beautiful supplication of the believers. They recognize that guidance is a gift from Allah, and they fear losing it. They ask Allah to keep their hearts firm on the straight path and not let them stray after being guided. The Prophet ﷺ used to frequently make this dua, showing that even the most righteous need Allah's constant protection from deviation.",
    "Grant us Your mercy": "They ask Allah for His special mercy—mercy that protects, guides, forgives, and blesses. This mercy comes directly from Allah's treasure and is given to those who sincerely seek it.",
    "You are indeed the Giver ˹of all bounties˺": "Allah is Al-Wahhab—the One who gives generously and continuously without expecting anything in return. He gives gifts of guidance, health, provision, family, and countless blessings. Recognizing this encourages us to always turn to Him for our needs."
  },
  9: {
    "Our Lord! You will certainly gather all humanity for the ˹promised˺ Day": "The believers affirm their faith in the Day of Judgment. They acknowledge that Allah will gather every human being who ever lived—from Adam to the last person—for accountability. No one will escape this gathering, regardless of when or where they lived or died.",
    "about which there is no doubt": "The Day of Judgment is an absolute certainty. There is no room for doubt about its occurrence. Just as Allah created everything from nothing, He will resurrect all of creation for judgment.",
    "Surely Allah does not break His promise": "Allah has promised this Day, and He never fails to fulfill His promises. Unlike humans who may forget, lie, or be unable to keep their word, Allah's promise is guaranteed. This gives hope to the oppressed that justice will come, and it warns the oppressors that they will be held accountable."
  },
  10: {
    "Indeed, neither the wealth nor children of the disbelievers will be of any benefit to them against Allah": "On the Day of Judgment, nothing that people value in this world will help them. Wealth cannot buy salvation, and children cannot intercede or take their place in punishment. The things people often chase after—money, status, family legacy—will be utterly useless when facing Allah's judgment. This is a wake-up call for those who prioritize worldly gains over their faith.",
    "and they will be the fuel for the Fire": "Those who persistently disbelieve and die in that state will become fuel for the Hellfire. This is a terrifying image meant to shake people out of their heedlessness. The very bodies that enjoyed worldly pleasures while rejecting Allah will burn in the Fire."
  },
  11: {
    "Their fate will be like that of the people of Pharaoh and those before them": "History repeats itself. The disbelievers of every era face similar consequences. The people of Pharaoh were drowned, the people of 'Ad were destroyed by wind, the people of Thamud were struck by a mighty blast—all because they rejected Allah's messengers and signs. The Quraysh of Makkah and all future disbelievers are warned through these historical examples.",
    "they all rejected Our signs, so Allah seized them for their sins": "Their destruction was not random or unjust—it was a direct consequence of their persistent denial of clear signs and their sins. Allah gives chances, sends warnings, and provides clear guidance. When people stubbornly reject all of this, they bring punishment upon themselves.",
    "And Allah is severe in punishment": "When Allah's punishment comes, it is complete and overwhelming. No one can resist it or escape it. This attribute should not make believers despair of His mercy but should make disbelievers fear continuing in their rejection."
  },
  12: {
    "˹O Prophet!˺ Tell the disbelievers, \"Soon you will be overpowered\"": "This was a prophecy given when Muslims were weak and few in Makkah, yet it came true. The Prophet ﷺ was commanded to warn the disbelievers that despite their current power and arrogance, they would be defeated. This prophecy was fulfilled at the Battle of Badr and ultimately with the conquest of Makkah.",
    "and driven to Hell": "Beyond their worldly defeat, they will be gathered and driven to Hellfire on the Day of Judgment. Their humiliation is not just temporary; it extends to eternity if they die in disbelief.",
    "what an evil place to rest!": "Hell is described sarcastically as a 'resting place'—but what a terrible place to rest! Instead of comfort and peace, it offers only torment and regret. This expression emphasizes how horrific the final destination of disbelievers will be."
  },
  13: {
    "Indeed, there was a sign for you in the two armies that met in battle": "The Battle of Badr (2 AH/624 CE) was a miraculous sign from Allah. A small, poorly equipped Muslim army of about 313 faced a well-armed Quraysh force of about 1,000. The Muslims' victory was a clear demonstration of Allah's power and support.",
    "one fighting for the cause of Allah and the other in denial": "The contrast could not be clearer—one group fought sincerely for Allah's cause, seeking His pleasure and the establishment of truth. The other fought to defend their idols, their pride, and to destroy Islam. The battle was between faith and disbelief.",
    "The believers saw their enemy twice their number": "Allah made the disbelievers appear larger in number to the believers as a test of their faith and courage. Despite seeing they were greatly outnumbered, the believers trusted in Allah and fought bravely. This shows that faith gives courage that defies logical calculations.",
    "But Allah supports with His victory whoever He wills": "Victory is not determined by numbers, weapons, or human calculations—it is granted by Allah to whomever He chooses. When Allah's help comes, a small group can defeat a mighty army. The believers should always seek Allah's support through faith, righteousness, and sincere supplication.",
    "Surely in this is a lesson for people of insight": "Those who have spiritual vision and understanding can extract powerful lessons from this event: that truth prevails over falsehood, that Allah's help is real, that faith is more powerful than material strength, and that perseverance in Allah's path brings victory. These lessons apply to every challenge believers face."
  },
  14: {
    "The enjoyment of ˹worldly˺ desires—women, children, treasures of gold and silver, fine horses, cattle, and fertile land—has been made appealing to people": "Allah describes the things that naturally attract human hearts: companionship and intimacy (women/spouses), family and legacy (children), wealth and luxury (gold and silver), status symbols and transportation (fine horses—today it would include luxury cars), livestock representing assets and business, and real estate (fertile land). These things are not evil in themselves—they are part of human nature and can be blessings when enjoyed within Allah's limits.",
    "These are the pleasures of this worldly life": "All these attractive things are temporary enjoyments of the present life. They will pass away, decay, or be left behind at death. The word 'mata' (enjoyment/provision) suggests something temporary that is used and then discarded—like supplies for a journey, not the final destination.",
    "but with Allah is the finest destination": "The best return, the finest home, the ultimate success is with Allah in the Hereafter. This world, with all its attractions, cannot compare to what Allah has prepared for the believers. This verse is not condemning worldly blessings but putting them in proper perspective—enjoy them within limits, be grateful for them, but never let them distract you from your true destination."
  },
  15: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Shall I inform you of what is better than ˹all of˺ this?\"": "After describing worldly attractions, Allah invites people to consider something far superior. This rhetorical question captures attention and creates anticipation—there is something better than all the gold, silver, spouses, children, and property of this world!",
    "Those mindful ˹of Allah˺ will have Gardens with their Lord under which rivers flow": "The people of Taqwa (God-consciousness) will receive Paradise—not just any garden, but gardens beneath which rivers flow, providing endless beauty, freshness, and pleasure. The mention of rivers indicates abundance, life, and constant renewal.",
    "to stay there forever": "Unlike worldly pleasures that end, Paradise is eternal. No fear of death, no worry about losing what you have, no aging or decay. Forever in bliss—this is the true success.",
    "and pure spouses": "The spouses in Paradise are purified from all physical and spiritual imperfections—no illness, no negative emotions, no disagreements. Pure companionship and perfect harmony.",
    "along with Allah's pleasure": "The greatest reward of all is mentioned last for emphasis—Allah's pleasure and approval (Ridwan). The Prophet ﷺ said that Allah will ask the people of Paradise if they are pleased, and they will say yes. Then Allah will say, 'I will give you something even better: My pleasure, and I will never be angry with you after this.' (Bukhari & Muslim). This pleasure of Allah is greater than Paradise itself.",
    "And Allah is All-Seeing of ˹His˺ servants": "Allah sees everything His servants do—their worship, their struggles, their sincerity, and their shortcomings. Nothing is hidden from Him, and He will reward each person according to what they deserve."
  },
  16: {
    "who pray, \"Our Lord! We have believed, so forgive our sins\"": "These righteous servants constantly turn to Allah in supplication. They acknowledge their faith and then ask for forgiveness—because even believers make mistakes and commit sins. This shows the proper attitude: confidence in one's faith combined with humility about one's shortcomings.",
    "and protect us from the torment of the Fire": "They do not take Paradise for granted. Despite their faith and good deeds, they fear the Fire and ask Allah for protection. This balance of hope and fear is the hallmark of true believers. The Prophet ﷺ and his companions, despite being promised Paradise, used to make this supplication frequently."
  },
  17: {
    "˹It is they˺ who are patient": "They demonstrate sabr (patience) in all circumstances—patience in obeying Allah's commands, patience in staying away from sins, and patience when facing difficulties and trials. Patience is a quality that covers all aspects of a believer's life.",
    "sincere": "They are truthful (sadiqeen) in their faith, their words, and their actions. There is no gap between what they believe, what they say, and what they do. They are genuine, not hypocritical.",
    "obedient": "They are qaniteen—devoutly obedient to Allah, humble in their worship, constantly engaged in acts of devotion. They maintain their prayers and other obligations consistently.",
    "and charitable": "They spend their wealth in Allah's cause—helping the poor, supporting good causes, and giving for the sake of Allah. They understand that their wealth is a trust from Allah and use it generously.",
    "and who pray for forgiveness before dawn": "They wake up in the last part of the night, the blessed time of Tahajjud (night prayer), to seek Allah's forgiveness. This is when most people are asleep, but these special servants sacrifice their sleep to stand before their Lord. Allah descends to the lowest heaven in the last third of the night and asks, 'Is there anyone seeking forgiveness so that I may forgive them?' (Bukhari & Muslim)."
  },
  18: {
    "Allah ˹Himself˺ is a Witness that there is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him": "The greatest testimony comes from Allah Himself—He bears witness to His own oneness. This is the most powerful and authoritative statement possible. Allah, with His perfect knowledge, declares that there is no true deity except Him.",
    "and so are the angels and people of knowledge": "Joining Allah in this testimony are the angels—pure beings who worship Allah constantly and have direct knowledge of the unseen—and the people of knowledge, the scholars and learned ones who have understood the truth through revelation and reflection. The association of scholars with angels in bearing this testimony shows the high status of Islamic knowledge.",
    "He is the Maintainer of justice": "Allah maintains perfect justice in His creation, His decrees, and His judgments. He does not wrong anyone even by an atom's weight. Everything He does is fair and balanced.",
    "There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him—the Almighty, All-Wise": "The declaration is repeated for emphasis and conclusion. Allah is Al-Aziz (Almighty, undefeatable) and Al-Hakeem (All-Wise, perfect in judgment). His power is guided by wisdom, and His wisdom is backed by absolute power."
  },
  19: {
    "Certainly, Allah's only Way is Islam": "Islam—meaning complete submission to Allah—is the only religion acceptable to Him. This has always been the true religion, from Adam through all the prophets to Muhammad ﷺ. The core message never changed: worship Allah alone and follow His guidance. Every prophet brought Islam in its essence.",
    "Those who were given the Scripture did not dispute ˹among themselves˺ out of mutual envy until knowledge came to them": "The Jews and Christians had clear knowledge from their scriptures, yet they divided into sects and disputed among themselves. Their disputes were not due to lack of knowledge but due to envy, arrogance, and worldly competition. When knowledge came, instead of uniting them, it became a tool for division because of their corrupt intentions.",
    "Whoever denies Allah's signs, then surely Allah is swift in reckoning": "Those who reject Allah's clear revelations and signs will face quick accountability. Allah's judgment comes faster than people expect. This is a warning not to take rejection of truth lightly."
  },
  20: {
    "So if they argue with you ˹O Prophet˺, say, \"I have submitted myself to Allah, and so have my followers.\"": "If people dispute or argue about religion, the Prophet ﷺ is instructed to simply declare his complete submission to Allah. No need for endless debates—the truth is clear. He and his followers have surrendered entirely to Allah's will.",
    "And ask those who were given the Scripture and the illiterate ˹people˺, \"Have you submitted yourselves ˹to Allah˺?\"": "This question is posed to both groups: the People of the Book (Jews and Christians) who have scriptures, and the unlettered Arabs who had no previous scripture. Both are invited to the same truth—submission to Allah alone. The invitation is universal.",
    "If they submit, they will be ˹rightly˺ guided": "Accepting Islam is the path to true guidance. When someone sincerely submits to Allah, they find the straight path and begin their journey toward eternal success.",
    "But if they turn away, then your duty is only to deliver ˹the message˺": "The Prophet's responsibility is to convey the message clearly, not to force anyone to accept. Guidance is ultimately from Allah. If people refuse, the Prophet ﷺ is not accountable for their choices. This is comforting for all callers to Islam—their job is to deliver the message with wisdom and good character, and the results are in Allah's hands.",
    "And Allah is All-Seeing of ˹His˺ servants": "Allah sees everyone—those who accept, those who reject, and the sincere effort of those who deliver His message. No one's actions escape His observation."
  },
  21: {
    "Indeed, those who deny Allah's signs": "Those who reject Allah's clear revelations and refuse to believe in His guidance have begun their path to destruction.",
    "kill the prophets unjustly": "Some people in history went so far as to murder the prophets sent to guide them—like some of the Children of Israel who killed prophets such as Zakariyya and Yahya (peace be upon them). These prophets brought nothing but truth and good, yet they were killed without any justifiable reason. This is among the greatest of crimes.",
    "and kill people who stand up for justice": "They also killed righteous people who commanded justice and fairness in society. Those who speak truth to power and call for justice are often targets of oppressors throughout history.",
    "give them good news of a painful punishment": "The phrase 'good news' is used sarcastically—instead of glad tidings, they receive the news of a painful, agonizing punishment. This rhetorical device emphasizes the certainty and severity of their punishment."
  },
  22: {
    "They are the ones whose deeds are wasted in this world and the Hereafter": "All their efforts, whatever good they may have done, will be completely nullified. Their disbelief and major sins cancel out any good deeds. In this world, they gain no true benefit, and in the Hereafter, they have nothing to show.",
    "And they will have no helpers": "On the Day of Judgment, no one will be able to help them—no friends, no family, no powerful allies. They will stand alone before Allah with no one to intercede for them or protect them from punishment."
  },
  23: {
    "Have you not seen those who were given a portion of the Scriptures?": "Allah draws attention to a specific group—those who received divine scripture (primarily referring to some of the Jewish scholars of Madinah). They had knowledge of Allah's revelation but failed to act upon it properly.",
    "Yet when they are invited to the Book of Allah to settle their disputes": "When disputes arose—whether about the Prophet's authenticity or legal matters—they were invited to let Allah's Book be the judge. The Torah itself contained prophecies about Prophet Muhammad ﷺ and laws that aligned with what he brought.",
    "some of them turn away heedlessly": "Despite having the knowledge, some of them deliberately turned away from Allah's judgment. They did not want the truth; they wanted rulings that favored their desires or interests. This shows how knowledge without sincerity leads to arrogance and rejection."
  },
  24: {
    "This is because they say, \"The Fire will not touch us except for a few days.\"": "They had developed a false sense of security. They believed that even if they sinned, they would only face temporary punishment—perhaps a few days—because of their lineage or chosen status. This is a dangerous delusion that many people fall into: believing they are special and will be exempt from consequences.",
    "They have been deceived in their faith by their wishful lying": "Their own lies and wishful thinking deceived them about their religion. When people invent beliefs that comfort their desires rather than seeking truth, they end up fooling themselves. True faith requires facing reality, not fabricating comfortable falsehoods."
  },
  25: {
    "But how ˹horrible˺ will it be when We gather them together on the Day about which there is no doubt": "This rhetorical question emphasizes the horror of that Day. Their false beliefs will not help them when they stand before Allah on the Day of Judgment—a Day that is absolutely certain to come.",
    "when every soul will be paid in full for what it has done": "Complete justice will be served. Every person will receive exactly what they earned—good for good, evil for evil. No deed will be forgotten or miscounted.",
    "and none will be wronged": "Allah's justice is perfect. No one will be punished for what they did not do, and no one will be denied reward for their good deeds. This is a comfort for the oppressed and a warning for the oppressors."
  },
  26: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O Allah! Lord over all authorities!\"": "This supplication addresses Allah as the Owner and Master of all dominion and sovereignty. Every king, president, ruler, and authority figure holds power only because Allah allowed it. He is the King of all kings.",
    "You give authority to whoever You please and remove it from who You please": "Allah grants power and authority according to His wisdom, and He takes it away when He wills. History is full of examples of great empires that rose and fell by Allah's permission. This should humble those in power and give hope to the oppressed.",
    "You honour whoever You please and disgrace who You please": "True honor and disgrace are in Allah's hands. Someone may be poor and unknown in this world but honored by Allah, while another may be rich and famous but disgraced in Allah's sight. The Prophet ﷺ said, 'Whoever seeks honor through other than Allah, Allah will disgrace him.'",
    "all good is in Your Hands": "Every form of good—provision, guidance, success, health, family, victory—comes from Allah. There is no source of good except Him. This creates complete dependence on and gratitude toward Allah.",
    "Surely You ˹alone˺ are Most Capable of everything": "Allah has unlimited power over all things. Nothing is difficult for Him. This supplication reminds believers that no matter how impossible something seems, Allah can make it happen."
  },
  27: {
    "You cause the night to pass into the day and the day into the night": "Allah controls the cosmic cycles that humans depend upon. The gradual transition between night and day, the changing of seasons—all of this is under His precise control. This happens so regularly that people take it for granted, but it is a constant miracle.",
    "You bring forth the living from the dead and the dead from the living": "Allah brings life from lifelessness—a living bird from a lifeless egg, a living plant from a dead seed, a living human from inanimate elements. And He brings death from life—showing His complete control over the cycle of existence. Some scholars also interpret this spiritually: bringing believers (spiritually alive) from disbelieving families (spiritually dead) and vice versa.",
    "And You provide for whoever You will without limit": "Allah's provision is unlimited. He gives abundantly to some and measures it for others according to His wisdom. But His storehouses never decrease—He provides without counting and without running out. This should make believers turn to Him alone for their needs and not despair of His mercy."
  },
  28: {
    "Believers should not take disbelievers as guardians instead of the believers": "Muslims are prohibited from taking disbelievers as their intimate allies, protectors, or close confidants in a way that compromises their faith or the interests of the Muslim community. This does not prohibit normal dealings, kindness, or just treatment of non-Muslims—those are commanded elsewhere in the Quran. What is forbidden is placing loyalty to disbelievers above loyalty to the Muslim community, or sharing secrets of the Muslims with those who oppose Islam.",
    "and whoever does so will have nothing to hope for from Allah": "Whoever takes such prohibited alliance, preferring disbelievers over believers in matters of loyalty and support, has cut themselves off from Allah's protection and guardianship. They have chosen the wrong side.",
    "unless it is a precaution against their tyranny": "There is an exception: if a Muslim is in a position of genuine danger and needs to outwardly show friendliness to protect themselves from persecution, this is permitted. The heart must remain firm in faith even if the tongue says what is necessary for survival. This shows Islam's flexibility in matters of genuine hardship.",
    "And Allah warns you about Himself": "This is a powerful warning—be cautious of Allah Himself. Fear His punishment, be mindful of His knowledge, and do not take His commands lightly. When Allah warns about Himself, it is the most serious warning possible.",
    "And to Allah is the final return": "Everyone will return to Allah for judgment. All alliances, all choices, all actions will be accounted for. This reminds believers to always keep the final destination in mind when making decisions."
  },
  29: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Whether you conceal what is in your hearts or reveal it, it is known to Allah.\"": "Nothing is hidden from Allah—not the thoughts in your mind, not the intentions in your heart, not the secrets you have never spoken. Whether you hide something or express it openly, Allah knows it completely. This is both a warning to those who harbor evil intentions and a comfort to those whose good deeds go unseen by people.",
    "For He knows whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth": "Allah's knowledge encompasses everything in existence—every atom, every creature, every event in the heavens and the earth. Nothing escapes His awareness.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable of everything": "Combined with His complete knowledge is His complete power. He knows all and can do all. This is why believers place their complete trust in Him."
  },
  30: {
    "˹Watch for˺ the Day when every soul will be presented with whatever good it has done": "On the Day of Judgment, all deeds will be brought forward and displayed. Every good deed, no matter how small, will be shown. This will bring joy to the believers who will see their prayers, charity, patience, and kindness recorded and rewarded.",
    "And it will wish that its misdeeds were far off": "When people see their sins and bad deeds presented, they will desperately wish there was a vast distance between themselves and those deeds. They will want to disown their own actions. This is the regret of that Day—but it will be too late.",
    "And Allah warns you about Himself": "Again, Allah gives this severe warning about Himself—be cautious of His punishment, His judgment, His knowledge. Take this warning seriously now, before it is too late.",
    "And Allah is Ever Gracious to ˹His˺ servants": "Despite the severe warnings, Allah concludes by reminding us of His compassion (Ra'oof). He warns us because He cares for us. His warnings are themselves a mercy—giving us the opportunity to repent and change before the Day when regret will be useless. He does not want to punish us; He wants us to save ourselves."
  },
  31: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"If you ˹sincerely˺ love Allah, then follow me\"": "This verse is known as the 'Verse of the Test' (Ayat al-Imtihan) because it provides the test for true love of Allah. Many people claim to love Allah, but the proof of that love is following the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ. Love without obedience is empty words. Following the Prophet's teachings, his Sunnah, his character, and his example is the evidence of genuine love for Allah.",
    "Allah will love you": "The reward for following the Prophet ﷺ is the greatest reward imaginable—Allah's love. When Allah loves a servant, He announces it to the angels, and love for that person is placed in the hearts of creation. Allah's love brings success, protection, guidance, and ultimately Paradise.",
    "and forgive your sins": "Along with Allah's love comes forgiveness. All the sins that burden the soul can be erased through sincere following of the Prophet ﷺ. This is incredible hope for those who have made mistakes.",
    "For Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Allah constantly forgives and shows mercy. His forgiveness covers all sins for those who sincerely repent and follow His guidance. His mercy is greater than His wrath."
  },
  32: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Obey Allah and His Messenger.\"": "The command is simple and direct: obey Allah and obey the Messenger. These two obediences go together—you cannot truly obey Allah while rejecting His Messenger, and following the Messenger is following Allah's commands. This is the foundation of Islamic practice.",
    "If they still turn away, then truly Allah does not like the disbelievers": "If after all the clear proofs, invitations, and explanations, people still turn away from obedience, then this is a sign of disbelief (kufr). And Allah does not love those who reject faith. Allah's love is for the believers, the obedient, the sincere—not for those who stubbornly reject the truth."
  },
  33: {
    "Indeed, Allah chose Adam, Noah, the family of Abraham, and the family of 'Imrân above all people ˹of their time˺": "Allah selected certain individuals and families for special honor and responsibility. Adam was the first human and prophet, chosen to be the father of humanity. Noah was chosen to carry the message through the great flood. The family of Abraham (Ibrahim) includes Ismail, Ishaq, Yaqub, and eventually Prophet Muhammad ﷺ—a blessed lineage of prophets. The family of 'Imran refers to the family of Maryam (Mary), which includes the prophets Zakariyya, Yahya (John), and Isa (Jesus). These were not chosen arbitrarily but because of their faith, righteousness, and Allah's perfect wisdom. Being 'chosen' brought responsibility, not just privilege."
  },
  34: {
    "They are descendants of one another": "These blessed families are connected—each generation passing the torch of faith to the next. The prophets were linked by blood and by mission, forming a continuous chain of guidance throughout human history. This shows the unity of the prophetic message.",
    "And Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing": "Allah hears every prayer, every supplication, every word spoken by His servants. He knows everything—who is sincere, who is deserving, who will carry the message faithfully. His choice of these individuals and families was based on His perfect knowledge of their hearts and their capabilities."
  },
  35: {
    "˹Remember˺ when the wife of 'Imrân said": "This refers to Hannah, the mother of Maryam (Mary). She was a righteous woman from a blessed family. The Quran begins narrating this beautiful story to show how Maryam came to be so special—it started with a devoted mother making a sincere vow to Allah.",
    "\"My Lord! I dedicate what is in my womb entirely to Your service\"": "Hannah made a vow (nadhr) to Allah that whatever child she was carrying would be dedicated entirely to the service of Allah and His temple (Bayt al-Maqdis in Jerusalem). In those times, children dedicated to the temple would serve there, freed from worldly occupations, focusing only on worship and religious duties. This was typically done with male children who could serve as priests.",
    "\"so accept it from me\"": "She humbly asked Allah to accept her offering. Despite her sincere intention, she understood that acceptance is from Allah alone. This teaches us that even our best efforts need Allah's acceptance—we should never assume our deeds are automatically accepted.",
    "\"You ˹alone˺ are truly the All-Hearing, All-Knowing\"": "She concluded her supplication by affirming Allah's attributes. He hears every prayer, even the silent ones in the heart, and He knows every intention behind every action. This shows her deep faith and proper etiquette in making dua."
  },
  36: {
    "When she delivered, she said, \"My Lord! I have given birth to a girl\"": "Hannah had expected a boy, as males were traditionally the ones who served in the temple. When she gave birth to a girl, she expressed this to Allah—not in complaint, but perhaps in concern about whether her vow could still be fulfilled.",
    "and Allah fully knew what she had delivered": "This is Allah's interjection, reminding us that He knew exactly what she delivered and His plan was greater than she could imagine. Allah knew that this girl would be more blessed than any boy could have been—she would become the mother of Prophet Isa (Jesus).",
    "\"and the male is not like the female\"": "Hannah acknowledged that boys and girls are different and have different roles. In her context, only males served in the temple. Little did she know that Allah would make her daughter more honored than any male servant of the temple.",
    "\"I have named her Mary\"": "The name Maryam means 'worshipper' or 'servant of Allah' in their language. This name reflected Hannah's hope that her daughter would be devoted to Allah's worship despite being female.",
    "\"and I seek Your protection for her and her offspring from Satan, the accursed\"": "This is a powerful supplication that every parent should learn from. Hannah sought Allah's protection for Maryam and her future descendants from Shaytan. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'There is no newborn except that Satan touches it when it is born, so it starts crying from Satan's touch, except Maryam and her son' (Bukhari). This shows that Allah answered Hannah's prayer in the most complete way."
  },
  37: {
    "So her Lord accepted her graciously": "Allah accepted Hannah's dedication of Maryam, even though she was female. This shows that sincerity is what matters to Allah, not gender or societal expectations. Allah honored this mother's intention in the most beautiful way.",
    "and blessed her with a pleasant upbringing": "Allah caused Maryam to grow up in the best possible manner—physically, spiritually, and morally. She was nurtured to become a woman of exceptional purity and devotion. The phrase suggests she grew like a beautiful plant, carefully tended by Allah's care.",
    "entrusting her to the care of Zachariah": "Prophet Zakariyya (Zachariah) became Maryam's guardian. He was a prophet and the husband of Maryam's aunt (or sister according to some narrations), making him the ideal caretaker. When the priests disputed about who should care for her, they cast lots, and Zakariyya was chosen by Allah's decree.",
    "Whenever Zachariah visited her in the sanctuary, he found her supplied with provisions": "Maryam had a special chamber in the temple for her worship. When Zakariyya would visit her, he would find food with her—fruits out of season, provisions that had no apparent source. This was a miracle, a special honor from Allah.",
    "He exclaimed, \"O Mary! Where did this come from?\"": "Zakariyya was amazed and curious. A prophet himself, he recognized this as something supernatural and asked Maryam about its source.",
    "She replied, \"It is from Allah. Surely Allah provides for whoever He wills without limit\"": "Maryam's answer shows her deep faith and understanding. She knew her provision came directly from Allah, and she reminded Zakariyya of Allah's unlimited power to provide. Her words were simple but profound—they would soon inspire Zakariyya to make his own special supplication."
  },
  38: {
    "Then and there Zachariah prayed to his Lord": "Seeing the miraculous provision Allah gave to Maryam inspired Zakariyya. He thought: if Allah can provide out-of-season fruits, surely He can grant me a child despite my old age and my wife's barrenness. This shows how witnessing Allah's blessings on others should increase our hope and encourage us to ask Allah for our own needs.",
    "saying, \"My Lord! Grant me—by your grace—righteous offspring\"": "Zakariyya asked for 'dhurriyyatan tayyibah'—good, pure, righteous offspring. He did not just ask for a child; he asked for a righteous child. This teaches us to be specific in our duas and to prioritize quality over mere quantity. He acknowledged it would be purely from Allah's grace, not something he deserved.",
    "\"You are certainly the Hearer of ˹all˺ prayers\"": "He ended his supplication by affirming Allah's attribute of hearing and answering prayers. This shows proper adab (etiquette) in dua—beginning with praise of Allah, asking with humility, and concluding with confidence in Allah's ability to respond."
  },
  39: {
    "So the angels called out to him while he stood praying in the sanctuary": "The answer to Zakariyya's prayer came while he was in the best possible state—standing in prayer in the sacred sanctuary. This shows that prayer is one of the best times to receive Allah's blessings and that our worship creates an atmosphere receptive to divine response.",
    "\"Allah gives you good news of ˹the birth of˺ John\"": "Allah responded with good news (bushra) of a son named Yahya (John). The name Yahya was chosen by Allah Himself, as mentioned in Surah Maryam—'We have not assigned this name to anyone before' (19:7). This was a unique honor for this unique child.",
    "\"who will confirm the Word of Allah\"": "Yahya would later confirm and testify to Isa (Jesus), who is called 'the Word of Allah' because he was created by Allah's command 'Be!' Yahya recognized Isa's prophethood and called people to believe in him.",
    "\"and will be a great leader\": ": "Yahya would be a 'sayyid'—a master, leader, and noble person. He would lead people in righteousness and be honored among his community.",
    "\"chaste\"": "He would be 'hasoor'—completely chaste, controlling his desires, devoting himself entirely to worship and his mission. Some scholars say he never married, dedicating himself fully to calling people to Allah.",
    "\"and a prophet among the righteous\"": "Yahya would be granted prophethood and would be counted among the righteous servants of Allah. This confirms his high status in Allah's sight."
  },
  40: {
    "Zachariah exclaimed, \"My Lord! How can I have a son when I am very old and my wife is barren?\"": "Zakariyya's question was not from doubt but from amazement and wonder. He was an elderly man—some narrations say over 90 years old—and his wife had been barren her entire life. He wanted to understand how this miracle would happen. It is natural to wonder at Allah's miracles even while believing in them.",
    "He replied, \"So will it be. Allah does what He wills\"": "The answer is simple yet profound: Allah does whatever He wills. No obstacle is too great for Him—not old age, not barrenness, not any physical limitation. When Allah decrees something, it happens. This is the same message that would be given to Maryam later about her own miraculous pregnancy."
  },
  41: {
    "Zachariah said, \"My Lord! Grant me a sign\"": "Zakariyya asked for a sign to confirm the pregnancy had begun and to increase his joy and certainty. Asking for signs to strengthen faith is permissible when done with sincerity, not from doubt.",
    "He said, \"Your sign is that you will not ˹be able to˺ speak to people for three days except through gestures\"": "Allah gave him a unique sign: he would be unable to speak to people for three days while remaining physically healthy. He could only communicate through gestures. This was both a sign and a preparation—a period of silence and reflection before the great blessing.",
    "\"Remember your Lord often\"": "During this period of silence from human speech, Zakariyya was instructed to increase his remembrance of Allah (dhikr). When we cannot speak to people, we can still speak to Allah through our hearts and tongues in worship.",
    "\"and glorify ˹Him˺ morning and evening\"": "He was commanded to engage in tasbeeh (glorification of Allah) at the blessed times of morning and evening. This shows that even in extraordinary circumstances, maintaining regular worship is essential."
  },
  42: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when the angels said, \"O Mary! Surely Allah has selected you\"": "The angels addressed Maryam directly, informing her of her special status. Allah chose her (istafa) for a unique honor that no other woman would receive—to be the mother of a great prophet born without a father.",
    "\"purified you\"": "Allah purified Maryam from all spiritual and physical impurities, from sins, and from anything that would diminish her honor. She was protected from Satan's touch from birth (as her mother had prayed), and she lived a life of exceptional chastity and devotion.",
    "\"and chosen you over all women of the world\"": "This is a remarkable statement: Maryam was chosen above all women of all time. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'The best women of Paradise are Khadijah bint Khuwaylid, Fatimah bint Muhammad, Maryam bint 'Imran, and Asiyah bint Muzahim (wife of Pharaoh)' (Ahmad). Among these, Maryam holds a unique position as the only woman with a chapter of the Quran named after her."
  },
  43: {
    "\"O Mary! Be devout to your Lord\"": "The angels instructed Maryam to be 'qanit'—deeply devoted, obedient, and humble before Allah. This was both recognition of her existing devotion and encouragement to continue and increase it.",
    "\"prostrate yourself ˹in prayer˺\"": "She was commanded to make sujood (prostration), the most humble position of worship where the forehead touches the ground before Allah. This is the closest a servant gets to Allah.",
    "\"and bow along with those who bow down\"": "She was to join the community of worshippers in rukoo' (bowing). This indicates both congregational worship and being part of the righteous community. Despite her special status, she was to remain part of the worshipping community, not isolated in pride."
  },
  44: {
    "This is news of the unseen that We reveal to you ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah addresses Prophet Muhammad ﷺ, confirming that this detailed story about Maryam and Zakariyya is knowledge of the unseen (ghayb) that only Allah could reveal. Muhammad ﷺ had no way of knowing these details except through divine revelation.",
    "You were not with them when they cast lots to decide who would be Mary's guardian": "When Maryam was brought to the temple, many priests wanted the honor of being her guardian. To decide fairly, they cast lots (threw their pens or arrows into water, and the one whose pen floated or behaved differently was chosen). Muhammad ﷺ was not present at this event that happened centuries before his birth.",
    "nor were you there when they argued ˹about it˺": "The Prophet ﷺ was not witness to their disputes and discussions. Yet the Quran narrates these events accurately. This is proof that the Quran is from Allah, not invented by Muhammad ﷺ. How could an unlettered man in Arabia know such details about events in Jerusalem centuries earlier?"
  },
  45: {
    "˹Remember˺ when the angels proclaimed, \"O Mary! Allah gives you good news of a Word from Him\"": "The angels brought Maryam the most extraordinary news—she would give birth to a special child described as 'a Word from Allah.' This title means Isa was created by Allah's command 'Be!' (Kun). It does not mean Isa is divine or part of Allah—it means he was created through a direct divine command without a human father.",
    "\"his name will be the Messiah, Jesus, son of Mary\"": "His name would be Al-Masih Isa—the Messiah Jesus. 'Masih' (Messiah) means 'the anointed one' or 'one who travels much' spreading guidance. Notice he is called 'son of Mary' (Ibn Maryam), not 'son of God.' Throughout the Quran, Isa is connected to his mother, affirming his human nature and his miraculous birth without a father.",
    "\"honoured in this world and the Hereafter\"": "Isa would be honored and respected in both worlds. In this world, millions follow him (though many misunderstand his message). In the Hereafter, he will have a high status near Allah as one of the greatest prophets.",
    "\"and he will be one of those nearest ˹to Allah˺\"": "Isa will be among those closest to Allah in rank and status—the elite of Allah's servants. This is the highest honor for any creation."
  },
  46: {
    "\"And he will speak to people in ˹his˺ infancy\"": "One of Isa's miracles was speaking clearly as a newborn baby in the cradle. This miracle defended his mother's honor when people accused her of immorality. The baby Isa declared his prophethood and his mother's innocence.",
    "\"and adulthood\"": "He would also speak with wisdom and guidance as an adult, fulfilling his prophetic mission by teaching people about Allah and calling them to righteousness.",
    "\"and will be one of the righteous\"": "Despite all his miracles and high status, Isa remained a righteous servant of Allah—not a god, not the son of God, but a blessed human prophet who submitted to Allah's will."
  },
  47: {
    "Mary wondered, \"My Lord! How can I have a child when no man has ever touched me?\"": "Maryam asked this question out of natural human wonder, not doubt. She was a virgin who had never been with any man. How could she possibly have a child? This confirms her purity and chastity—she herself testified that no man had touched her.",
    "An angel replied, \"So will it be. Allah creates what He wills\"": "The answer, like the one given to Zakariyya, points to Allah's unlimited power. Allah is not bound by natural laws—He created those laws and can bypass them whenever He wills. Creating a child without a father is easy for the One who created Adam without father or mother.",
    "\"When He decrees a matter, He simply tells it, 'Be!' And it is!\"": "This is the ultimate expression of Allah's power: His command 'Kun' (Be). When Allah decides something, He does not need materials, time, or assistance. He simply commands it to exist, and it exists. Isa was created by this divine command, making him a miraculous sign but not divine himself."
  },
  48: {
    "\"And Allah will teach him writing and wisdom\"": "Allah would grant Isa knowledge of writing and deep wisdom (hikmah). Wisdom means understanding the true nature of things, applying knowledge correctly, and having insight into divine matters. This prepared him for his prophetic mission.",
    "\"the Torah and the Gospel\"": "Isa would be taught the Torah (the scripture of Musa) so he could confirm and uphold its true teachings, and he would be given the Gospel (Injeel)—a new revelation containing guidance and light. The Gospel was not a book written by others about Isa; it was revelation given directly to him."
  },
  49: {
    "\"and ˹make him˺ a messenger to the Children of Israel\"": "Isa was sent specifically to the Children of Israel (the Jews) who had strayed from the true teachings of their prophets. His mission was to bring them back to the straight path and to prepare them for the final messenger who would come after him.",
    "\"˹to proclaim,˺ 'I have come to you with a sign from your Lord'\"": "Isa announced his prophethood with clear signs (miracles) that proved his divine mission. These were not magic tricks but genuine miracles granted by Allah to authenticate his message.",
    "\"I will make for you a bird from clay, breathe into it, and it will become a ˹real˺ bird—by Allah's Will\"": "Isa would fashion a shape of a bird from clay, blow into it, and by Allah's permission, it would become a living bird. This miracle demonstrated creative power, but notice the crucial phrase: 'by Allah's Will.' Isa did not do this by his own power; he was merely a channel for Allah's miracles.",
    "\"I will heal the blind and the leper\"": "Isa would cure those born blind (who had never seen) and those with leprosy (considered incurable in those times). These miracles showed Allah's power over disease and disability.",
    "\"and raise the dead to life—by Allah's Will\"": "The greatest of his miracles: bringing dead people back to life. Again, 'by Allah's Will' is emphasized—Isa did not possess this power independently. He was a servant through whom Allah displayed His power.",
    "\"And I will prophesize what you eat and store in your houses\"": "Isa could tell people what they had eaten and what they had stored in their homes—knowledge they had not shared with anyone. This demonstrated knowledge of the unseen granted to him by Allah.",
    "\"Surely in this is a sign for you if you ˹truly˺ believe\"": "These miracles were sufficient proof of his prophethood for anyone with a sincere heart. The condition 'if you truly believe' indicates that miracles only benefit those who approach with openness and sincerity."
  },
  50: {
    "\"And I will confirm the Torah revealed before me\"": "Isa did not come to abolish the Torah but to confirm its original message. He upheld the true teachings of Musa while correcting the distortions that had crept in over time.",
    "\"and legalize some of what had been forbidden to you\"": "Part of Isa's mission was to ease some of the strict regulations that had been placed on the Children of Israel as punishment for their previous sins. Allah, in His mercy, lightened their burden through Isa.",
    "\"I have come to you with a sign from your Lord\"": "Isa repeatedly emphasized that his authority and miracles came from Allah. He was a messenger, not the source of the message.",
    "\"so be mindful of Allah and obey me\"": "The call was clear: have taqwa (consciousness of Allah) and follow the prophet. Obedience to the messenger is obedience to Allah because the messenger only conveys what Allah commands."
  },
  51: {
    "\"Surely Allah is my Lord and your Lord\"": "This is the definitive statement of Isa's message, completely refuting any claim of his divinity. Isa clearly declared that Allah is HIS Lord—meaning Isa himself worshipped Allah. If Isa was God, how could he have a Lord? This verse alone disproves the Christian doctrine of Trinity.",
    "\"So worship Him ˹alone˺\"": "The command is exclusive worship of Allah—not Isa, not Mary, not any saint or creation. This was the message of every prophet from Adam to Muhammad ﷺ.",
    "\"This is the Straight Path\"": "Worshipping Allah alone is the sirat al-mustaqeem—the straight path that leads to salvation. Every deviation from this—whether worshipping Isa, idols, or anything else—is a deviation from the straight path."
  },
  52: {
    "When Jesus sensed disbelief from his people": "Despite all the miracles and clear proofs, Isa perceived that the majority of his people were rejecting him and disbelieving. This must have been deeply painful—a prophet seeing his own community turn away from the truth.",
    "he asked, \"Who will stand up with me for Allah?\"": "In this moment of trial, Isa called for sincere supporters—not just casual followers, but those who would stand firm for Allah's cause regardless of opposition. This is a call every prophet made at some point.",
    "The disciples replied, \"We will stand up for Allah\"": "The Hawariyyun (disciples) responded with commitment. The word suggests they were sincere, purified supporters. They pledged their support not to Isa personally, but to Allah's cause.",
    "\"We believe in Allah, so bear witness that we have submitted\"": "They declared their faith and asked Isa to witness that they were Muslims—those who had submitted to Allah. This confirms that Islam (submission to Allah) was the religion of Isa's true followers, not Christianity as it later developed."
  },
  53: {
    "˹They prayed to Allah,˺ \"Our Lord! We believe in Your revelations\"": "The disciples turned to Allah in prayer, affirming their belief in what He had revealed. Their faith was in Allah's revelation, not in personalities.",
    "\"and follow the messenger\"": "They confirmed their obedience to Isa as Allah's messenger. Following the messenger is the practical expression of believing in the revelation.",
    "\"so count us among those who bear witness\"": "They asked Allah to record them among the witnesses—those who testify to the truth and will testify on the Day of Judgment. This is a supplication for sincerity and steadfastness until the end."
  },
  54: {
    "And the disbelievers made a plan ˹against Jesus˺": "The enemies of Isa—among the Jewish leaders who rejected him—conspired to have him killed. They plotted with the Roman authorities, seeking to crucify him and end his mission.",
    "but Allah also planned": "While they schemed, Allah had His own plan. Human plots, no matter how cunning, cannot overcome Allah's decree. Allah was fully aware of their conspiracy and had already determined the outcome.",
    "and Allah is the best of planners": "Allah's plan always prevails. He is 'Khayrul Makireen'—the best of those who plan. His plan saved Isa from crucifixion and humiliated those who thought they had succeeded."
  },
  55: {
    "˹Remember˺ when Allah said, \"O Jesus! I will take you\"": "The word 'mutawaffeeka' has been interpreted by scholars. Some say it means 'I will cause you to die' (naturally, after you return at the end of times), while most scholars say it means 'I will take you completely' or 'I will take you in soul and body.' The Islamic belief is that Isa was not crucified; Allah raised him bodily to the heavens.",
    "\"and raise you up to Myself\"": "Allah raised Isa up to Himself, to the heavens. According to Islamic belief, Isa is alive in heaven and will return before the Day of Judgment to complete his mission, kill the Dajjal (Antichrist), and live as a follower of the final law (Shariah of Muhammad ﷺ).",
    "\"I will deliver you from those who disbelieve\"": "Allah purified Isa from the plots of disbelievers. They could not harm him. The Quran states clearly: 'They did not kill him, nor did they crucify him, but it was made to appear so to them' (4:157).",
    "\"and elevate your followers above the disbelievers until the Day of Judgment\"": "Those who truly follow Isa's message of monotheism (which is what Muslims believe) will remain elevated above those who rejected him. This can be understood spiritually (in truth and guidance) and sometimes physically (in worldly dominance).",
    "\"Then to Me you will ˹all˺ return, and I will settle all your disputes\"": "Everyone—Isa's followers, those who rejected him, and everyone in between—will return to Allah for final judgment. All the disputes about who Isa was and what he taught will be settled definitively. The truth will be made clear."
  },
  56: {
    "\"As for those who disbelieve, I will subject them to a severe punishment in this life and the Hereafter\"": "Those who reject faith will face severe consequences in both worlds. In this life, they may face various trials, humiliation, or divine punishment. In the Hereafter, they will face the Fire. Disbelief has consequences that cannot be escaped.",
    "\"and they will have no helpers\"": "On the Day of Judgment, no one will be able to help the disbelievers—no friends, no family, no powerful allies. They will stand alone before Allah with no one to intercede or rescue them."
  },
  57: {
    "\"And as for those who believe and do good, they will be rewarded in full\"": "The believers who combine faith with righteous actions will receive their complete reward without any reduction. Allah does not diminish anyone's reward—in fact, He multiplies good deeds many times over.",
    "\"And Allah does not like the wrongdoers\"": "Allah's justice means He does not love those who wrong themselves through disbelief or who wrong others through oppression. This dislike translates to punishment for those who persist in wrongdoing without repentance."
  },
  58: {
    "We recite ˹all˺ this to you ˹O Prophet˺ as one of the signs": "Allah tells Prophet Muhammad ﷺ that this narration about Isa, Maryam, and the events surrounding them is a sign—evidence of the Quran's divine origin. Muhammad ﷺ had no access to these detailed accounts except through revelation.",
    "and ˹as˺ a wise reminder": "The Quran is described as a 'wise reminder' (dhikr hakeem)—it contains wisdom and serves to remind people of the truth. These stories are not entertainment; they carry profound lessons for every generation."
  },
  59: {
    "Indeed, the example of Jesus in the sight of Allah is like that of Adam": "This verse provides a powerful logical argument against those who claim Isa is divine because he had no father. The comparison with Adam destroys this argument completely. Adam had no father AND no mother—yet no one claims Adam is God or son of God.",
    "He created him from dust, then said to him, \"Be!\" And he was!": "Allah created Adam from dust, then commanded him to exist, and Adam came into being. Similarly, Isa was created by the command 'Be!'—no father required. If being created without a father makes someone divine, then Adam has an even stronger claim to divinity (which is absurd). This proves that Isa's miraculous birth was simply Allah's power, not evidence of divinity."
  },
  60: {
    "This is the truth from your Lord": "What the Quran narrates about Isa is the absolute truth from Allah. It is not speculation, mythology, or human opinion. It is divine revelation that settles the matter once and for all.",
    "so do not be one of those who doubt": "This is a command to the Prophet ﷺ and through him to all Muslims: do not have any doubt about this truth. The matter of Isa's nature is clear—he was a noble prophet and servant of Allah, not divine in any way."
  },
  61: {
    "Now, whoever disputes with you ˹O Prophet˺ concerning Jesus after full knowledge has come to you": "After all the clear explanations about Isa's true nature, if anyone still argues and disputes, it is not due to lack of information but due to stubbornness and rejection of truth.",
    "say, \"Come! Let us gather our children and your children, our women and your women, ourselves and yourselves\"": "This is the famous verse of Mubahala (mutual imprecation). It was revealed when a Christian delegation from Najran came to debate with the Prophet ﷺ about Isa. When they refused to accept the truth, this challenge was issued: both parties would gather with their families.",
    "\"then let us sincerely invoke Allah's curse upon the liars\"": "Both parties would pray to Allah to curse whoever was lying about Isa. This is a serious matter—invoking Allah's curse on oneself if lying. The Christian delegation, despite their claims, refused to participate in this Mubahala because they feared the consequences. Their refusal indicated they were not confident in their own beliefs when it came to such a serious test."
  },
  62: {
    "Certainly, this is the true narrative": "Everything the Quran has narrated about Isa, Maryam, and the prophets is the absolute truth. There is no doubt, no embellishment, no error.",
    "and there is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Allah": "The conclusion and core message: only Allah deserves worship. Not Isa, not Maryam, not any creation. This is the message of every prophet and the message of the Quran.",
    "And indeed, Allah ˹alone˺ is the Almighty, All-Wise": "Allah possesses all power and all wisdom. His decisions are perfect, His revelation is true, and His plan always prevails."
  },
  63: {
    "If they turn away": "If after all the clear proofs and the challenge of Mubahala, they still turn away from the truth, then they are choosing corruption over guidance.",
    "then surely Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of the corruptors": "Allah knows those who spread corruption and reject truth. Nothing is hidden from Him. They may escape accountability in this world, but Allah's knowledge guarantees that justice will come."
  },
  64: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O People of the Book! Let us come to common terms\"": "This is a beautiful invitation to dialogue based on shared principles. Instead of focusing on differences, the Quran calls Jews and Christians to unite on common ground. This shows Islam's reasonable and balanced approach to interfaith relations.",
    "\"that we will worship none but Allah\"": "The first common term: pure worship of Allah alone. This is something the original Torah and Gospel taught before they were altered. All Abrahamic faiths should agree on this fundamental point.",
    "\"associate none with Him\"": "The second term: no partners with Allah. No Trinity, no divine sons, no intermediaries who share in Allah's divinity. Pure, uncompromised monotheism.",
    "\"nor take one another as lords instead of Allah\"": "The third term: not elevating human beings—whether priests, rabbis, monks, or saints—to a position where they can make things halal or haram, or where they are obeyed absolutely as if they were God. When the Prophet ﷺ recited this verse, his companion Adi ibn Hatim (a former Christian) said they did not worship their priests. The Prophet ﷺ explained that when people follow their religious leaders in making forbidden things permissible (or vice versa), that is a form of worship.",
    "But if they turn away, then say, \"Bear witness that we have submitted ˹to Allah alone˺\"": "If they refuse this invitation to common ground, Muslims should make their own position clear: we have submitted to Allah alone. The invitation was sincere; if rejected, Muslims continue on the straight path regardless."
  },
  65: {
    "O People of the Book! Why do you argue about Abraham": "Both Jews and Christians claimed Ibrahim as one of their own—Jews said he was Jewish, Christians said he followed their way. But this is historically impossible and logically absurd.",
    "while the Torah and the Gospel were not revealed until long after him?": "Ibrahim lived centuries before Musa (who received the Torah) and Isa (who received the Gospel). How could Ibrahim be a Jew or Christian when these religions (in their later, named forms) did not exist in his time? This is a simple logical argument that exposes the fallacy of their claims.",
    "Do you not understand?": "Allah appeals to their reason. Basic timeline knowledge shows their claims are false. True understanding would lead them to recognize that Ibrahim followed pure monotheism—submission to Allah—which is what Islam is."
  },
  66: {
    "Here you are! You disputed about what you have ˹little˺ knowledge of": "They argued about matters from their own scriptures where they at least had some knowledge (even if limited or distorted).",
    "but why do you now argue about what you have no knowledge of?": "But regarding Ibrahim, who lived before their scriptures, they have no knowledge at all. They are arguing based on nothing but wishful thinking and invented claims.",
    "Allah knows and you do not know": "The final authority on Ibrahim's religion is Allah, who knows everything. Human speculation cannot replace divine knowledge. The Quran, as Allah's final revelation, provides the definitive answer."
  },
  67: {
    "Abraham was neither a Jew nor a Christian": "This is the definitive statement. Ibrahim was not Jewish (Judaism came through the law of Musa, generations later) and not Christian (Christianity came through Isa, even more generations later).",
    "he submitted in all uprightness": "Ibrahim was a 'Hanif'—one who turned away from all false religions toward pure monotheism. He was inclined only toward the truth, rejecting the idol worship of his society.",
    "and was not a polytheist": "Ibrahim rejected all forms of shirk (associating partners with Allah). He famously destroyed the idols of his people and argued against polytheism. He was a pure monotheist—a Muslim in the true sense of the word."
  },
  68: {
    "Indeed, those who have the best claim to Abraham are his followers": "The closest people to Ibrahim are not necessarily his biological descendants, but those who follow his way—pure monotheism and submission to Allah.",
    "this Prophet": "Prophet Muhammad ﷺ has the greatest claim to Ibrahim because he revived and perfected the message of pure monotheism that Ibrahim taught. The Prophet ﷺ is on the same path, completing the mission of all previous prophets.",
    "and the believers": "The Muslims—those who submit to Allah alone—are the true inheritors of Ibrahim's legacy. They follow his religion: rejecting idolatry, worshipping Allah alone, and submitting to His will.",
    "And Allah is the Guardian of those who believe": "Allah is the Wali (protector, supporter, guardian) of the believers. Those who follow the true path of Ibrahim are under Allah's care and protection. This is the greatest honor and security anyone could have."
  },
  69: {
    "Some of the People of the Book wish to mislead you ˹believers˺": "A faction among the Jews and Christians actively desired to lead Muslims astray from their faith. Their motives included jealousy of the new Muslim community, fear of losing religious authority, and unwillingness to accept a prophet from outside their lineage. This was not all of them—the Quran is careful to say 'some' or 'a group.'",
    "They mislead none but themselves": "Their plots and schemes actually harm no one but themselves. When someone tries to mislead others from the truth, they accumulate sins and distance themselves further from guidance. The believers, protected by Allah, remain on the straight path.",
    "yet they fail to perceive it": "They are so consumed by their desire to harm the believers that they do not realize they are destroying themselves. This is a common pattern: those who plot evil often cannot see that their plotting will backfire. They think they are clever, but they are the ultimate losers."
  },
  70: {
    "O People of the Book! Why do you reject the signs of Allah": "Allah directly addresses them with a penetrating question. They had clear signs—prophecies in their own scriptures about Prophet Muhammad ﷺ, the miraculous nature of the Quran, and the truth they could see with their own eyes.",
    "while you bear witness ˹to their truth˺?": "The tragedy is that they themselves witnessed the truth of these signs. Their own scholars recognized Muhammad ﷺ from the descriptions in their books 'as they recognize their own sons' (2:146). Yet despite this inner recognition, they chose to reject. This makes their disbelief even more blameworthy—it was not ignorance but willful rejection."
  },
  71: {
    "O People of the Book! Why do you mix the truth with falsehood": "They engaged in a particularly dangerous form of deception: mixing truth with falsehood. This makes the falsehood harder to detect because it is wrapped in elements of truth. For example, they acknowledged some prophets while rejecting others, or accepted parts of revelation while distorting other parts.",
    "and hide the truth knowingly?": "Beyond mixing truth with falsehood, they actively concealed the truth—including the prophecies about Muhammad ﷺ in their scriptures. They knew what they were hiding; this was deliberate suppression of truth for worldly gains or tribal pride. Such knowing concealment is among the gravest sins."
  },
  72: {
    "A group among the People of the Book said ˹to one another˺, \"Believe in what has been revealed to the believers in the morning\"": "This verse exposes a calculated conspiracy. Some Jewish leaders in Madinah devised a plan: pretend to accept Islam at the beginning of the day, making a public show of conversion.",
    "\"and reject it in the evening, so they may abandon their faith\"": "Then, by the end of the day, publicly renounce Islam, claiming they found flaws in it. Their hope was that Muslims, especially new or weak believers, would think: 'If these learned scholars of previous scriptures left Islam after examining it, maybe there is something wrong with it.' This psychological warfare was designed to create doubt and cause Muslims to apostatize. Allah exposed this plot, rendering it ineffective."
  },
  73: {
    "\"And only believe those who follow your religion.\"": "They instructed each other to only trust and accept those who follow their own religion, creating an exclusive club that rejected outsiders regardless of truth.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Surely, ˹the only˺ true guidance is Allah's guidance.\"": "The Prophet ﷺ is instructed to respond: real guidance comes from Allah alone, not from tribal or religious allegiances. Truth is not determined by who says it but by its source—and the source of all truth is Allah.",
    "˹They also said,˺ \"Do not believe that someone will receive ˹revealed˺ knowledge similar to yours or argue against you before your Lord.\"": "They could not accept that prophethood and revelation could come to someone outside their community. They believed they had exclusive rights to divine favor and could not conceive of others receiving similar blessings.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Indeed, all bounty is in the Hands of Allah—He grants it to whoever He wills.\"": "The response destroys their exclusivist thinking: Allah gives His bounty—including prophethood, knowledge, and guidance—to whomever He chooses. No group has a monopoly on Allah's favor. He is not bound by human expectations of tribal privilege.",
    "\"And Allah is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing\"": "Allah's bounty is vast (Wasi') and He knows (Aleem) exactly who deserves it. His choices are based on His perfect wisdom, not human prejudices."
  },
  74: {
    "He chooses whoever He wills to receive His mercy": "Allah's special mercy—including prophethood, guidance, knowledge, and spiritual gifts—is given according to His choice. He chose Muhammad ﷺ as the final prophet, and no amount of jealousy or plotting can change that divine decree.",
    "And Allah is the Lord of infinite bounty": "Allah possesses boundless favor (fadl 'atheem). His treasures never diminish. He can bless whomever He wills without taking from others. The jealousy of some people toward others' blessings is therefore irrational—Allah has enough for everyone."
  },
  75: {
    "There are some among the People of the Book who, if entrusted with a stack of gold, will readily return it": "The Quran is fair and balanced. It acknowledges that some People of the Book are trustworthy and honest. If you give them a large fortune to hold, they will return it faithfully. These are people of integrity regardless of religious differences.",
    "Yet there are others who, if entrusted with a single coin, will not repay it unless you constantly demand it": "Others among them are dishonest even with small amounts. They will try to keep even a single dinar unless you persistently pressure them for it. Their dishonesty is not due to need but to corrupt character.",
    "This is because they say, \"We are not accountable for ˹exploiting˺ the Gentiles.\"": "They justified their dishonesty with a religious excuse: they believed that non-Jews (whom they called 'Ummiyyeen' or Gentiles) had no rights that they needed to respect. They thought cheating outsiders was permissible, even acceptable.",
    "And ˹so˺ they attribute lies to Allah knowingly": "This justification was a lie they invented and attributed to Allah. God never permitted cheating anyone based on their ethnicity or religion. By claiming divine sanction for their dishonesty, they committed the grave sin of lying about Allah—and they knew they were lying."
  },
  76: {
    "Absolutely!": "This is a strong refutation of their false claim. Absolutely, there is accountability! No one is exempt from moral obligations based on the ethnicity or religion of the other party.",
    "Those who honour their trusts and shun evil": "The correct approach is to fulfill all commitments and avoid wrongdoing regardless of whom you are dealing with. Trustworthiness (fulfilling covenants and trusts) and taqwa (being mindful of Allah and avoiding evil) are inseparable in Islam.",
    "surely Allah loves those who are mindful ˹of Him˺": "The ultimate reward for honesty and God-consciousness is Allah's love. This is the greatest achievement any human can attain. Those who maintain integrity because they fear Allah will earn His love and pleasure."
  },
  77: {
    "Indeed, those who trade Allah's covenant and their oaths for a fleeting gain": "Some people sell their religious commitments and their solemn oaths for worldly benefits—money, status, power, or other temporary gains. They break promises made to Allah and lie under oath for material profit. The word 'fleeting' (qaleel) emphasizes how worthless these gains are compared to what they sacrifice.",
    "will have no share in the Hereafter": "They forfeit their portion of Paradise. Whatever they gained in this world will disappear, and they will have nothing in the eternal life to come. This is the worst trade anyone could make.",
    "Allah will neither speak to them": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will not speak to them with words of mercy or kindness. This is a terrifying form of divine rejection—to be ignored by the Creator on the Day when everyone desperately needs His favor.",
    "nor look at them": "Allah will not look at them with mercy. This turning away from them by Allah is a punishment in itself, signifying complete rejection and disgrace.",
    "nor purify them on the Day of Judgment": "They will not be cleansed of their sins or declared innocent. They will remain in their spiritual filth, facing judgment without any purification or forgiveness.",
    "And they will suffer a painful punishment": "Beyond these forms of rejection, they will also experience active, painful punishment in Hell. The description is comprehensive: no share of good, no mercy, no purification, and eternal torment."
  },
  78: {
    "There are some among them who distort the Book with their tongues": "A group among the People of the Book engaged in verbal distortion—twisting their tongues while reading scripture to change its meaning. This could mean mispronouncing words to alter meanings, or using misleading intonation, or verbally adding to or subtracting from the text while reciting.",
    "to make you think this ˹distortion˺ is from the Book—but it is not what the Book says": "Their goal was to deceive listeners into thinking these distortions were actually part of the original scripture. Unsuspecting people would believe they were hearing God's word when they were actually hearing human fabrications.",
    "They say, \"It is from Allah\"—but it is not from Allah": "They went further by explicitly claiming divine authority for their distortions. This is the height of religious fraud—attributing human words to Allah.",
    "And ˹so˺ they attribute lies to Allah knowingly": "This was not accidental error or misunderstanding. They knew exactly what they were doing. They consciously and deliberately lied about what Allah had revealed. This knowing fabrication is among the gravest sins because it corrupts religion at its source."
  },
  79: {
    "It is not appropriate for someone who Allah has blessed with the Scripture, wisdom, and prophethood to say to people, \"Worship me instead of Allah.\"": "This verse addresses a fundamental truth: no true prophet would ever ask people to worship him. A person blessed with scripture, wisdom, and prophethood knows Allah better than anyone and would never claim divinity. This indirectly refutes the claim that Isa (Jesus) asked to be worshipped—if he truly was a prophet (which Muslims affirm), he would never have made such a claim.",
    "Rather, he would say, \"Be devoted to the worship of your Lord ˹alone˺\"": "A true prophet calls people to Allah, not to himself. He says: become 'Rabbaniyyin'—people who are devoted to the Lord (Rabb), who are deeply knowledgeable about their religion, and who act upon that knowledge. This is what every prophet taught.",
    "in accordance with what these prophets read in the Scripture and what they taught": "This devotion to Allah is based on what the prophets taught from their scriptures. The prophets themselves were students and teachers of divine revelation. They read the scripture, understood it, taught it, and lived by it—all pointing people to Allah, never to themselves."
  },
  80: {
    "And he would never ask you to take angels and prophets as lords": "A prophet would never command people to worship angels (as some Arabs did) or to worship other prophets (as Christians worship Isa). Taking any creation as 'lord' (rabb) is a form of shirk that no prophet would endorse.",
    "Would he ask you to disbelieve after you have submitted?": "This is a rhetorical question emphasizing the absurdity of the claim. Would a prophet—whose mission is to bring people to faith—command them to commit the ultimate act of disbelief (worshipping other than Allah) after they have already submitted to Allah? This makes no sense. Therefore, any claim that prophets asked to be worshipped is false."
  },
  81: {
    "˹Remember˺ when Allah made a covenant with the prophets": "Allah took a solemn covenant from all the prophets—a binding agreement that had significant implications for their followers as well.",
    "˹saying,˺ \"Now that I have given you the Book and wisdom, if there comes to you a messenger confirming what you have, you must believe in him and support him.\"": "The content of the covenant: after receiving revelation and wisdom, if another messenger comes who confirms their message, they and their followers must believe in and support that messenger. This refers primarily to Prophet Muhammad ﷺ, who confirmed the core message of all previous prophets. This covenant obligates the followers of all prophets to accept Muhammad ﷺ when he came.",
    "He added, \"Do you affirm this covenant and accept this commitment?\"": "Allah asked them to explicitly confirm their acceptance. This was not a passive agreement but an active acknowledgment of the responsibility.",
    "They said, \"Yes, we do.\"": "All the prophets affirmed the covenant. Every prophet from Adam to Isa agreed to this condition.",
    "Allah said, \"Then bear witness, and I too am a Witness.\"": "Both the prophets and Allah Himself are witnesses to this covenant. This makes it the most binding agreement possible. The followers of previous prophets cannot claim ignorance—their own prophets agreed to accept the final messenger."
  },
  82: {
    "Whoever turns back after this, they will be the rebellious": "Anyone who rejects this covenant after knowing about it—refusing to accept Muhammad ﷺ despite the clear evidence and the agreement of their own prophets—is classified as 'fasiq' (rebellious, corrupt). They have broken the divine covenant and will face the consequences."
  },
  83: {
    "Do they desire a way other than Allah's": "This is a rhetorical question expressing amazement. How could anyone seek a religion or way of life other than what Allah has prescribed? What alternative could possibly be better than guidance from the Creator?",
    "knowing that all those in the heavens and the earth submit to His Will, willingly or unwillingly": "Everything in creation submits to Allah—the sun, moon, stars, mountains, trees, animals, and all beings. Some submit willingly (like the angels, righteous believers, and obedient creation) while others submit unwillingly (like disbelievers who, despite their rejection, cannot escape Allah's cosmic laws and will eventually submit on the Day of Judgment).",
    "and to Him they will ˹all˺ be returned": "Everyone and everything will return to Allah for judgment. There is no escape from this return. Given this reality, why would anyone choose a path other than submission to the One they will inevitably face?"
  },
  84: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"We believe in Allah\"": "The foundation of Islamic faith begins with belief in Allah—the One true God, with all His perfect names and attributes.",
    "\"and what has been revealed to us\"": "Muslims believe in the Quran, the final revelation given to Prophet Muhammad ﷺ.",
    "\"and what was revealed to Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and his descendants\"": "Muslims believe in the revelations given to Ibrahim, Ismail, Ishaq, Yaqub, and the tribes of Israel (the Asbat). We accept all authentic divine guidance that came to them.",
    "\"and what was given to Moses, Jesus, and other prophets from their Lord\"": "Muslims believe in the original Torah given to Musa, the original Gospel given to Isa, and the revelations given to all other prophets. We do not reject any true prophet or any authentic revelation.",
    "\"we make no distinction between any of them\"": "Unlike others who accept some prophets and reject others, Muslims believe in all of them equally as messengers of Allah. We do not say Musa was a prophet but Isa was not, or Isa was a prophet but Muhammad ﷺ was not. All are honored and believed.",
    "\"and to Him we ˹fully˺ submit\"": "The ultimate expression of this belief is complete submission (Islam) to Allah. Faith is not just intellectual acknowledgment but practical surrender to Allah's will."
  },
  85: {
    "Whoever seeks a way other than Islam": "Anyone who chooses a religion or way of life other than Islam—other than complete submission to Allah according to His final guidance through Muhammad ﷺ—has made a catastrophic choice.",
    "it will never be accepted from them": "Allah will not accept any other religion. This is absolute and final. No matter how sincere someone may be in a false religion, sincerity does not make falsehood true. The criteria for acceptance is following Allah's prescribed way.",
    "and in the Hereafter they will be among the losers": "The consequences extend to eternity. Those who reject Islam will be among the losers on the Day of Judgment—losing Paradise, losing Allah's pleasure, and losing everything that truly matters."
  },
  86: {
    "How will Allah guide a people who chose to disbelieve after they had believed": "This rhetorical question expresses divine amazement at such people. They had tasted the sweetness of faith, experienced the light of guidance, and then deliberately turned away. How can such people expect further guidance?",
    "acknowledged the Messenger to be true": "They had testified that Prophet Muhammad ﷺ was indeed a true messenger from Allah. Their apostasy was not due to doubt but to other factors—arrogance, worldly interests, or desire.",
    "and received clear proofs": "They had seen undeniable evidence—miracles, the Quran's eloquence, the Prophet's character, fulfilled prophecies—yet still turned away. Their rejection was willful, not based on lack of evidence.",
    "For Allah does not guide the wrongdoing people": "When people choose wrongdoing (dhulm) despite knowing the truth, Allah does not force guidance upon them. He allows them to go astray as a consequence of their own choice. This is divine justice—not arbitrary, but based on their willful rejection."
  },
  87: {
    "Their reward is that they will be condemned by Allah, the angels, and all of humanity": "The punishment for apostasy after clear guidance is comprehensive: Allah's curse (la'nah) upon them, which means being distanced from His mercy; the curse of all the angels; and the curse of all humanity. On the Day of Judgment, even their fellow disbelievers will curse them. This is total rejection from all quarters."
  },
  88: {
    "They will be in Hell forever": "Their destination is eternal. There is no exit, no parole, no second chance after death. The word 'khalideen' (forever) emphasizes the permanence of their punishment.",
    "Their punishment will not be lightened": "Unlike worldly punishments that may decrease over time or with good behavior, their punishment remains constant in its severity. There is no relief, no reduction, no getting used to it.",
    "nor will they be delayed ˹from it˺": "They will not be given respite or delay. The punishment begins immediately and continues without pause. They cannot ask for postponement or temporary relief."
  },
  89: {
    "As for those who repent afterwards and mend their ways": "Even after such severe warnings, the door of repentance remains open during one's lifetime. Those who sincerely return to faith (tawbah) and correct their behavior (islah) can still be saved. This shows Allah's immense mercy—even apostates can be forgiven if they genuinely repent.",
    "then surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Allah is Ghafoor (All-Forgiving) and Raheem (Most Merciful). His forgiveness can cover even the greatest sins when met with sincere repentance. This verse provides hope while maintaining the seriousness of the warning."
  },
  90: {
    "Indeed, those who disbelieve after having believed then increase in disbelief": "This describes those who apostatize and then continue to go deeper into disbelief—adding more sins, more rejection, and more opposition to Islam. Their disbelief grows rather than diminishes.",
    "their repentance will never be accepted": "Scholars explain this in different ways: (1) Their repentance at the time of death will not be accepted, as death-bed repentance when one sees the angels of death is too late. (2) They become so hardened in disbelief that they will never sincerely repent—and insincere repentance is not accepted. (3) If they persist in this state until death, there is no repentance accepted in the Hereafter.",
    "It is they who are astray": "Such people are the truly lost ones (dalleen). They had the truth, left it, and went deeper into error. They are the furthest from guidance."
  },
  91: {
    "Indeed, if each of those who disbelieve then die as disbelievers were to offer a ransom of enough gold to fill the whole world": "This powerful imagery illustrates the hopelessness of their situation. Imagine offering all the gold that could fill the entire earth—mountains of gold beyond imagination—as ransom to escape punishment.",
    "it would never be accepted from them": "Even this unimaginable wealth would be rejected. On the Day of Judgment, no material wealth has any value. The currency of the Hereafter is faith and good deeds, not gold and silver. All the treasures of the world cannot purchase a moment's relief from Hell.",
    "It is they who will suffer a painful punishment": "Their punishment is described as 'aleem' (painful, agonizing). The physical and psychological torment of Hell is beyond human comprehension.",
    "and they will have no helpers": "No one will come to their aid—no friends, no family, no wealth, no allies. They will face their punishment alone, with no one to intercede, no one to share the burden, and no one to rescue them. This is the ultimate consequence of dying in a state of disbelief."
  },
  92: {
    "You will never achieve righteousness until you donate some of what you cherish": "This profound verse establishes a criterion for true righteousness (birr). It is not enough to give away what you do not want or what is easy to part with. True righteousness is achieved when you give from what you love—your best wealth, your favorite possessions, your most valuable assets. When the companions heard this verse, Abu Talha immediately donated his most beloved garden, Bayruha, which was his finest property in Madinah. This is the standard: giving that costs you something dear, not just giving leftovers.",
    "And whatever you give is certainly well known to Allah": "Nothing escapes Allah's knowledge. He knows exactly what you give, how much it means to you, what your intention was, and whether it was truly from what you cherish. This encourages sincerity—give for Allah's sake, knowing He sees and records everything. It also provides comfort: even if no one else appreciates your sacrifice, Allah knows and will reward accordingly."
  },
  93: {
    "All food was lawful for the children of Israel": "Originally, all foods were permissible for the Children of Israel. There were no complex dietary restrictions from the beginning.",
    "except what Israel made unlawful for himself before the Torah was revealed": "Israel (Prophet Yaqub/Jacob) personally avoided certain foods—reportedly camel meat and milk—due to a personal vow or health reason (some narrations mention he had sciatica and vowed to avoid certain foods if Allah healed him). This was his personal choice, not a divine law.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Bring the Torah and read it, if your claims are true\"": "Some Jews claimed that their dietary restrictions were ancient laws from Ibrahim's time, implying that Islam's different dietary laws were innovations. The Prophet ﷺ is instructed to challenge them: bring your Torah and show where these restrictions are from Ibrahim. They could not do so because the restrictions came later, as punishments or as Yaqub's personal choice. This challenge silenced them and exposed their false claims."
  },
  94: {
    "Then whoever still fabricates lies about Allah, they will be the ˹true˺ wrongdoers": "After this clear challenge and proof, anyone who continues to attribute false laws to Allah is a wrongdoer (dhalim). They wrong themselves by persisting in falsehood, they wrong others by misleading them, and they wrong the truth by suppressing it. Lying about Allah is among the gravest sins."
  },
  95: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Allah has declared the truth\"": "After refuting their false claims, the Prophet ﷺ is to affirm that Allah's account is the truth. Whatever the Quran states about history, law, and religion is accurate.",
    "So follow the Way of Abraham, the upright": "The solution is to return to the pure, original religion of Ibrahim—the Hanif way. 'Hanif' means one who turns away from all falsehood toward pure monotheism. Ibrahim's way was simple, pure worship of Allah without the later additions, distortions, and sectarian disputes.",
    "who was not a polytheist": "Ibrahim was absolutely free from any form of shirk. He did not worship idols, did not take partners with Allah, and did not follow the polytheistic practices of his society. His religion was pure tawheed (monotheism)—and that is what Islam represents."
  },
  96: {
    "Surely the first House ˹of worship˺ established for humanity is the one at Bakkah": "The Kaaba in Makkah (also called Bakkah) is the first house of worship ever built for all humanity. According to authentic narrations, it was originally built by angels, then rebuilt by Adam, and later reconstructed by Ibrahim and Ismail. Some Jews claimed that Bayt al-Maqdis (Jerusalem) was more ancient and sacred, but this verse clarifies that the Kaaba preceded it by centuries.",
    "a blessed sanctuary": "The Kaaba and its surrounding area (the Haram) are blessed by Allah. Prayers there are multiplied, sins are forgiven, and spiritual blessings abound. The Prophet ﷺ said one prayer in Masjid al-Haram equals 100,000 prayers elsewhere.",
    "and a guide for ˹all˺ people": "The Kaaba serves as guidance for all humanity—a physical direction (qiblah) for prayer and a spiritual center that unites Muslims worldwide. It reminds people of pure monotheism, the legacy of Ibrahim, and the universal nature of Islam."
  },
  97: {
    "In it are clear signs": "The Sacred Mosque contains numerous clear signs of Allah's power and the truth of Islam. These include the miraculous preservation of the Kaaba throughout history, the constant flow of pilgrims, the spiritual atmosphere, and various historical markers.",
    "and the standing-place of Abraham": "The Maqam Ibrahim is a stone that bears the footprints of Prophet Ibrahim from when he stood on it while building the Kaaba. This physical artifact has been preserved for thousands of years as a sign and reminder of Ibrahim's devotion.",
    "Whoever enters it should be safe": "The Haram (sacred precinct) is a sanctuary where people should be safe. Even in pre-Islamic Arabia, this sanctity was largely respected—fighting was forbidden there, and even enemies would not attack each other within its boundaries. This safety is a divine law that should be honored.",
    "Pilgrimage to this House is an obligation by Allah upon whoever is able among the people": "Hajj is one of the five pillars of Islam, obligatory once in a lifetime for every Muslim who has the physical ability and financial means to perform it. The phrase 'whoever is able' includes health, wealth, safety of travel, and other practical considerations.",
    "And whoever disbelieves, then surely Allah is not in need of ˹any of His˺ creation": "Those who deny this obligation or refuse to perform Hajj despite being able only harm themselves. Allah is completely self-sufficient (Ghani). He does not need our worship—we need it for our own benefit. If someone refuses to perform Hajj, Allah loses nothing; the person loses everything."
  },
  98: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O People of the Book! Why do you deny the revelations of Allah\"": "The Prophet ﷺ is instructed to directly confront them with this question. They claim to believe in God and revelation, yet they deny the Quran and the signs proving Muhammad's prophethood. This is a fundamental contradiction.",
    "when Allah is a Witness to what you do?\"": "They may hide their true intentions from people, but Allah sees everything—their plots, their discussions, their inner thoughts. This reminder should make them fear, knowing that their denial is being recorded and will be brought against them on the Day of Judgment."
  },
  99: {
    "Say, \"O People of the Book! Why do you turn the believers away from the Way of Allah\"": "Beyond their own rejection, they actively tried to mislead Muslims—creating doubts, spreading misinformation, and attempting to weaken Muslim faith. This is a graver sin than personal disbelief.",
    "striving to make it ˹appear˺ crooked": "They tried to present Islam as crooked, defective, or false when it is actually straight and true. They distorted facts, misrepresented Islamic teachings, and spread propaganda to make the straight path seem bent.",
    "while you are witnesses ˹to its truth˺?": "The worst part is that many of them actually knew the truth. They recognized Muhammad ﷺ from their scriptures, they saw the miracles, they witnessed the transformation of society—yet they still opposed Islam and tried to make others leave it.",
    "And Allah is never unaware of what you do\"": "Allah is fully aware of every scheme, every whisper, every plot against Islam. Nothing escapes His knowledge. This is both a warning to them and a comfort to believers who might feel overwhelmed by such opposition."
  },
  100: {
    "O believers! If you were to yield to a group of those who were given the Scripture": "Allah directly warns the believers about the danger of following certain people from the People of the Book. Not all of them are the same, but a group among them has harmful intentions.",
    "they would turn you back from belief to disbelief": "Their goal is to make Muslims abandon their faith. Through various means—creating doubts, reviving old tribal conflicts, spreading false information—they seek to lead Muslims back to disbelief. This was seen in Madinah when some Jews tried to reignite the ancient enmity between the Aws and Khazraj tribes to divide the Muslim community."
  },
  101: {
    "How can you disbelieve when Allah's revelations are recited to you": "This rhetorical question expresses amazement. How could Muslims possibly fall into disbelief when they have the Quran—Allah's perfect guidance—being recited to them regularly? The Quran is protection, light, and guidance.",
    "and His Messenger is in your midst?": "Even more, the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ himself was living among them, teaching, guiding, and exemplifying the truth. With such direct access to revelation and its living embodiment, there should be no excuse for going astray. (For later generations, we have the Quran and the Sunnah, which continue to guide us.)",
    "Whoever holds firmly to Allah is surely guided to the Straight Path": "The key to protection is holding firmly to Allah—through faith, worship, obedience, and trust. Those who make Allah their support, their reference, and their refuge will be guided to the straight path and protected from misguidance."
  },
  102: {
    "O believers! Be mindful of Allah in the way He deserves": "This is a call to have taqwa (God-consciousness) at its highest level—to be constantly aware of Allah, to obey Him fully, to avoid all that He has forbidden, and to be grateful for His blessings. Some scholars say this was later made easier by the verse 'Fear Allah as much as you are able' (64:16), while others say both remain valid—striving for the highest level while understanding human limitations.",
    "and do not die except in ˹a state of full˺ submission ˹to Him˺": "This does not mean you can control when you die, but rather that you should live your entire life as a Muslim so that whenever death comes, you die in that state. The command is to maintain your Islam constantly, never abandoning it, so that your final state is one of submission to Allah. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'Whoever's last words are La ilaha illallah will enter Paradise.'"
  },
  103: {
    "And hold firmly to the rope of Allah": "The 'rope of Allah' refers to His religion, the Quran, and the community of believers. Just as a rope rescues someone from drowning or falling, holding to Allah's guidance saves from misguidance and destruction. This requires active effort—gripping tightly, not loosely.",
    "and do not be divided": "Unity is a divine command. Muslims must not split into warring factions, sects that hate each other, or groups that prioritize their differences over their common faith. Division weakens the community and pleases the enemies of Islam.",
    "Remember Allah's favour upon you when you were enemies, then He united your hearts, so you—by His grace—became brothers": "This directly addressed the Aws and Khazraj tribes of Madinah who had been at war for over a century. Islam transformed these bitter enemies into loving brothers. This transformation was not through human effort alone—it was Allah's grace that united their hearts. Such unity is a miracle and blessing that should never be taken for granted.",
    "And you were at the brink of a fiery pit and He saved you from it": "Before Islam, they were on the edge of destruction—destruction in this world through endless war, and destruction in the Hereafter through disbelief. Islam pulled them back from both disasters. This imagery of standing at the edge of Hell and being saved should create deep gratitude.",
    "This is how Allah makes His revelations clear to you, so that you may be ˹rightly˺ guided": "Allah explains His signs clearly so that people may find and follow the straight path. Understanding these blessings should motivate continued obedience and unity."
  },
  104: {
    "Let there be a group among you who call ˹others˺ to goodness": "There must always be a group in the Muslim community dedicated to calling people to good—to Islam, to righteousness, to beneficial actions. This is the mission of scholars, preachers, teachers, and every Muslim according to their ability.",
    "encourage what is good": "Enjoining ma'roof (what is good, recognized as virtuous by Islam and sound minds) is a community obligation. This includes encouraging prayer, honesty, kindness, justice, and all forms of righteousness.",
    "and forbid what is evil": "Forbidding munkar (what is evil, rejected by Islam and sound minds) is equally important. This means speaking against sin, injustice, and wrongdoing according to one's ability—with the hand (for those in authority), with the tongue (through speech), or at minimum with the heart (internal rejection).",
    "it is they who will be successful": "Those who fulfill this duty are the truly successful ones (muflihoon). Success is not measured by worldly achievement but by fulfilling one's purpose and earning Allah's pleasure."
  },
  105: {
    "And do not be like those who split ˹into sects˺ and differed after clear proofs had come to them": "This is a warning against following the pattern of previous nations—particularly the Jews and Christians—who divided into sects after receiving clear guidance. Their divisions were not due to lack of knowledge but due to envy, arrogance, and worldly interests. Muslims must learn from their mistakes.",
    "It is they who will suffer a tremendous punishment": "Those who cause division in the ummah after clear guidance has come will face severe punishment. Unity in truth is a religious obligation; division is a sin with serious consequences."
  },
  106: {
    "On that Day some faces will be bright while others gloomy": "On the Day of Judgment, people's states will be visible on their faces. The believers' faces will be radiant, bright, and beautiful—reflecting the light of faith and the joy of salvation. The disbelievers' faces will be dark, gloomy, and miserable—reflecting their inner darkness and impending doom.",
    "To the gloomy-faced it will be said, \"Did you disbelieve after having believed?\"": "This question is addressed to those who apostatized—who had tasted faith but then rejected it. Their crime is worse because they knew the truth and abandoned it. The question is rhetorical, meant to increase their shame and regret.",
    "So taste the punishment for your disbelief": "They will be told to taste the punishment they earned through their disbelief. The word 'taste' suggests direct, personal experience of the consequences they brought upon themselves."
  },
  107: {
    "As for the bright-faced, they will be in Allah's mercy": "Those whose faces shine with the light of faith will enter Allah's mercy—Paradise. This is described as 'Allah's mercy' because no one enters Paradise purely by their deeds; it is ultimately Allah's mercy that admits them.",
    "where they will remain forever": "Their reward is eternal. Unlike worldly pleasures that end, the bliss of Paradise never diminishes, never gets boring, and never concludes. This permanence is part of what makes it so precious."
  },
  108: {
    "These are Allah's revelations We recite to you ˹O Prophet˺ in truth": "These verses about the Day of Judgment, about reward and punishment, are from Allah and contain nothing but truth. They are not meant to frighten people unjustly but to inform them of reality.",
    "And Allah desires no injustice to ˹His˺ creation": "Allah does not want to wrong anyone. The punishments described are not arbitrary cruelty but just consequences of people's own choices. Allah has provided guidance, warning, and opportunity to repent. Those who suffer punishment have only themselves to blame."
  },
  109: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth": "Everything in existence belongs to Allah. He is the true Owner of all creation. This reminds us that we own nothing permanently—we are merely trustees of what Allah has lent us.",
    "And to Allah ˹all˺ matters will be returned ˹for judgment˺": "Every matter, every deed, every dispute will ultimately return to Allah for final judgment. There is no escaping this accountability. Knowing this should motivate us to act righteously and prepare for that Day."
  },
  110: {
    "You are the best community ever raised for humanity": "This is a tremendous honor bestowed upon the Muslim ummah. But it is conditional—the reasons for this excellence are mentioned immediately after. This honor comes with responsibility, not entitlement.",
    "you encourage good, forbid evil, and believe in Allah": "Three qualities make this community the best: (1) Enjoining what is good—actively promoting righteousness, (2) Forbidding what is evil—actively opposing wrongdoing, and (3) Believing in Allah—having correct faith as the foundation. Without these qualities, the honor is not deserved.",
    "Had the People of the Book believed, it would have been better for them": "If the Jews and Christians had accepted Islam, it would have been to their own benefit—salvation in the Hereafter and guidance in this life. Their rejection only harmed themselves.",
    "Some of them are faithful, but most are rebellious": "The Quran is fair—it acknowledges that some among the People of the Book do believe and are righteous. However, the majority are rebellious (fasiqoon)—they reject the truth and disobey Allah's commands."
  },
  111: {
    "They can never inflict harm on you, except a little annoyance": "Allah reassures the believers that the enemies cannot cause them serious harm. They may annoy with words, insults, or minor troubles, but they cannot destroy the Muslim community or its faith. This promise has proven true throughout history.",
    "But if they meet you in battle, they will flee and they will have no helpers": "When actual conflict occurs, Allah promises that the enemies will turn and run. They will be defeated and will find no one to help them. This was fulfilled at Badr, at the conquest of Makkah, and in countless other instances."
  },
  112: {
    "They will be stricken with disgrace wherever they go": "As a consequence of their rejection and crimes, humiliation follows them. Throughout history, when they abandoned their covenant with Allah, they faced subjugation and disgrace.",
    "unless they are protected by a covenant with Allah or a treaty with the people": "Their only security comes through returning to Allah's covenant (faith and obedience) or through treaties and agreements with others. Without these protections, they remain vulnerable.",
    "They have invited the displeasure of Allah and have been branded with misery": "They brought Allah's anger upon themselves through their choices. Misery (maskanah) clings to them—not because Allah is unjust, but because of their own actions.",
    "for rejecting Allah's revelations and murdering ˹His˺ prophets unjustly": "The specific crimes mentioned are: denying Allah's signs and revelations, and killing prophets who came to guide them. These are among the most heinous crimes possible.",
    "This is ˹a fair reward˺ for their disobedience and violations": "Their punishment is not arbitrary—it is a direct result of their disobedience and transgression. They violated Allah's commands and exceeded all bounds, and the consequences followed."
  },
  113: {
    "Yet they are not all alike": "The Quran is just and does not generalize unfairly. Not all People of the Book are the same—there are good and bad among them, just as in any community.",
    "there are some among the People of the Book who are upright": "A group among them stands firm on truth and righteousness. These are people of integrity who follow the best of their tradition and, when exposed to Islam, recognize and accept it.",
    "who recite Allah's revelations throughout the night, prostrating ˹in prayer˺": "These righteous ones spend their nights in worship—reciting scripture and praying. This describes those who accepted Islam from among the People of the Book, or those who were sincere worshippers waiting for the final prophet."
  },
  114: {
    "They believe in Allah and the Last Day": "Their faith includes belief in Allah and in the Day of Judgment—two fundamental pillars that motivate righteous action.",
    "encourage good and forbid evil": "They actively promote righteousness and oppose wrongdoing in their communities—the same qualities that make the Muslim ummah excellent.",
    "and race with one another in doing good": "They compete and hasten in performing good deeds, not wanting to miss any opportunity for righteousness. This eagerness distinguishes them from the lazy and complacent.",
    "They are ˹truly˺ among the righteous": "Such people are counted among the righteous (saliheen)—a noble category that includes prophets and their true followers."
  },
  115: {
    "They will never be denied the reward for any good they have done": "Every good deed they perform will be acknowledged and rewarded. Allah does not waste the efforts of anyone who does good sincerely. Not a single act of kindness, worship, or righteousness goes unnoticed.",
    "And Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of those mindful ˹of Him˺": "Allah knows exactly who has taqwa—who is truly conscious of Him and strives to please Him. This knowledge ensures that the righteous will receive their full reward."
  },
  116: {
    "Indeed, neither the wealth nor children of the disbelievers will be of any benefit to them against Allah": "The things people typically rely on for security—money and family—will be utterly useless against Allah's judgment. Wealth cannot buy forgiveness, and children cannot take their parents' place in punishment.",
    "It is they who will be the residents of the Fire": "Their permanent address will be Hell. The word 'ashab' (companions/residents) suggests they belong there, as if it were made for them.",
    "They will be there forever": "Their stay in Hell is eternal—no release, no parole, no end to the punishment for those who die in disbelief."
  },
  117: {
    "The good they do in this worldly life is like the harvest of an evil people struck by a bitter wind, destroying it ˹completely˺": "This powerful parable illustrates the fate of disbelievers' deeds. Imagine a people who planted crops, worked hard, and expected a good harvest. But because of their wrongdoing, a freezing, destructive wind came and destroyed everything. All their effort was wasted. Similarly, disbelievers may do charitable acts in this world, but without faith, these deeds will not benefit them in the Hereafter—they will be destroyed like that harvest.",
    "Allah never wronged them, but they wronged themselves": "Allah is not unjust in rejecting their deeds. They wronged themselves by building on the wrong foundation—deeds without faith. They had the opportunity to believe but refused. The loss is entirely their own doing."
  },
  118: {
    "O believers! Do not associate closely with others who would not miss a chance to harm you": "'Bitanah' refers to inner circle, close confidants, advisors—people you trust with secrets and rely upon for counsel. Muslims are warned not to take such intimate allies from among those who wish them harm.",
    "Their only desire is to see you suffer": "These people want nothing but trouble for the believers. They hope for Muslim failure, loss, and suffering. Why would one take such people as close advisors?",
    "Their prejudice has become evident from what they say": "Their hatred sometimes slips out in their speech—sarcastic comments, subtle insults, expressions of displeasure at Muslim success. These verbal slips reveal their true feelings.",
    "and what their hearts hide is far worse": "What they conceal in their hearts is even more intense than what they express. Their inner hatred far exceeds their outward expressions. This should be a cause for caution.",
    "We have made Our revelations clear to you, if only you understood": "Allah has provided clear guidance on this matter. Those who use their intellect will heed this warning and be careful about whom they trust."
  },
  119: {
    "Here you are! You love them but they do not love you": "This addresses the Muslims' good nature—they genuinely care for and try to befriend people who secretly despise them. The relationship is one-sided.",
    "and you believe in all Scriptures": "Muslims believe in all divine scriptures—the Torah, Gospel, and Quran. This comprehensive faith should earn them respect, yet these people still hate them.",
    "When they meet you they say, \"We believe.\"": "In person, they pretend to be friends or even believers. They say what Muslims want to hear, hiding their true feelings.",
    "But when alone, they bite their fingertips in rage": "In private, their hatred consumes them. Biting fingertips is an expression of extreme frustration and anger. They cannot bear to see Muslims prospering.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"˹May you˺ die of your rage!\"": "This is a powerful response—let them perish in their anger if they refuse to change. Their rage will destroy them, not the Muslims.",
    "Surely Allah knows best what is ˹hidden˺ in the heart": "Nothing is hidden from Allah. He knows their secrets, their plots, and their true intentions. This knowledge ensures justice will be served."
  },
  120: {
    "When you ˹believers˺ are touched with good, they grieve": "Any blessing that comes to Muslims—victory, prosperity, unity, growth—causes them distress. They cannot stand to see Muslims succeed.",
    "but when you are afflicted with evil, they rejoice": "Conversely, any hardship Muslims face—defeat, loss, difficulty—makes them happy. This reveals the sickness in their hearts.",
    "˹Yet,˺ if you are patient and mindful ˹of Allah˺, their schemes will not harm you in the least": "The antidote to their plotting is sabr (patience) and taqwa (God-consciousness). With these qualities, Muslims are protected from the harm of enemy schemes. Allah becomes their defender.",
    "Surely Allah is Fully Aware of what they do": "Allah's knowledge encompasses all their actions. Nothing they plot escapes His awareness, and He will deal with them accordingly."
  },
  121: {
    "˹Remember, O Prophet,˺ when you left your home in the early morning to position the believers in the battlefield": "This begins the account of the Battle of Uhud (3 AH). The Prophet ﷺ left Madinah early in the morning to organize the Muslim forces at Mount Uhud. He strategically positioned the fighters, including placing archers on a hill with strict instructions not to leave their posts.",
    "And Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing": "Allah heard all the discussions, consultations, and plans. He knew everyone's intentions—the sincere and the hypocritical, the brave and the cowardly. This reminder sets the context for the lessons that follow."
  },
  122: {
    "˹Remember˺ when two groups among you ˹believers˺ were about to cower": "Two groups from the Muslim army—the tribes of Banu Salamah and Banu Harithah—almost lost courage and considered retreating. Human weakness appeared even among sincere believers.",
    "then Allah reassured them": "Despite their momentary weakness, Allah was their Protector (Wali). He strengthened their hearts and they did not actually flee. Later, these tribes were not ashamed of this moment because Allah mentioned He was their protector.",
    "So in Allah let the believers put their trust": "The lesson is clear: believers must rely on Allah, not on their own strength or numbers. Trust in Allah (tawakkul) is the source of courage and steadfastness in difficulty."
  },
  123: {
    "Indeed, Allah made you victorious at Badr when you were ˹vastly˺ outnumbered": "Before discussing the setbacks at Uhud, Allah reminds the believers of Badr. They were only 313 against about 1000 well-equipped enemies, yet they won decisively. This was purely Allah's help.",
    "So be mindful of Allah, perhaps you will be grateful": "The lesson from Badr should inspire taqwa (mindfulness of Allah) and gratitude. Victory comes from Allah, not from numbers or equipment. Being grateful means remembering Allah's past help and trusting Him for the future."
  },
  124: {
    "˹Remember, O Prophet,˺ when you said to the believers, \"Is it not enough that your Lord will send down a reinforcement of three thousand angels for your aid?\"": "At Badr, when the believers felt anxious about the enemy's numbers, the Prophet ﷺ encouraged them with the promise of angelic support. Three thousand angels would descend to fight alongside them. This promise boosted their morale and confidence."
  },
  125: {
    "Most certainly, if you ˹believers˺ are firm and mindful ˹of Allah˺ and the enemy launches a sudden attack on you": "The conditions for increased divine support are: sabr (patience, firmness, steadfastness) and taqwa (mindfulness of Allah). If the enemy attacks and the believers maintain these qualities...",
    "Allah will reinforce you with five thousand angels designated ˹for battle˺": "The support increases to five thousand angels, specially marked or designated for combat. These angels were real participants in the battle, striking fear into the enemy and directly engaging in combat. The word 'musawwimeen' suggests they were marked or distinguished in some way."
  },
  126: {
    "Allah ordained this ˹reinforcement˺ only as good news for you and reassurance for your hearts": "The promise of angels served multiple purposes: it was good news (bushra) that lifted their spirits, and it was reassurance (tuma'ninah) that calmed their hearts. Knowing that Allah's angels were fighting alongside them gave them courage and peace.",
    "And victory comes only from Allah—the Almighty, All-Wise": "Ultimately, victory is from Allah alone. Not from numbers, not from weapons, not even from angels—but from Allah who commands all these things. He is Al-Aziz (Almighty, undefeatable) and Al-Hakeem (All-Wise, making perfect decisions about who deserves victory and when)."
  },
  127: {
    "to destroy a group of the disbelievers": "One purpose of the victory at Badr was to cut off (destroy, kill, weaken) a portion of the disbelieving forces. Many of the Quraysh leaders were killed at Badr, significantly weakening their leadership and morale.",
    "and humble the rest, causing them to withdraw in disappointment": "Those who survived were humiliated and discouraged. They retreated, having failed in their objective to destroy the Muslims. This disappointment (khaybah) was both military and psychological—they realized they could not easily defeat the believers who had Allah's support."
  },
  128: {
    "You ˹O Prophet˺ have no say in the matter": "This verse was revealed when the Prophet ﷺ was injured at Uhud and, in his pain, prayed against some of the enemies. Allah clarified that even the Prophet ﷺ has no authority over who receives mercy or punishment—that belongs exclusively to Allah. This is a profound lesson: even the most beloved to Allah does not control divine decisions about people's fate.",
    "It is up to Allah to turn to them in mercy or punish them": "Allah may choose to guide some enemies to repentance and forgive them, or He may punish them for their crimes. Both options remain with Him. Indeed, many of those who fought against Muslims at Uhud later became Muslims and were forgiven.",
    "for indeed they are wrongdoers": "Regardless of their ultimate fate, their current state is one of wrongdoing (dhulm). They have wronged themselves through disbelief and wronged others through their aggression. Allah acknowledges their crime while retaining authority over their judgment."
  },
  129: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth": "Allah owns everything in existence. As the Owner, He has complete authority over His creation. No one can question His decisions or override His will.",
    "He forgives whoever He wills, and punishes whoever He wills": "This is Allah's prerogative alone. His forgiveness is based on His wisdom—often connected to repentance, faith, and good deeds. His punishment is also based on wisdom—connected to persistent disbelief and wrongdoing. But ultimately, He decides.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful": "Despite His power to punish, Allah emphasizes His forgiveness and mercy. These attributes are mentioned to encourage people to seek His forgiveness rather than despair. His mercy is His dominant attribute."
  },
  130: {
    "O believers! Do not consume interest, multiplying it many times over": "This is a direct prohibition of riba (usury/interest). The pre-Islamic practice involved lending money and, when the borrower could not pay on time, doubling and redoubling the debt. This exploitative practice trapped people in endless cycles of debt. While this verse mentions the extreme form, all forms of riba are prohibited in other verses (2:275-279). Interest-based systems harm the poor, create economic instability, and violate principles of justice.",
    "And be mindful of Allah, so you may prosper": "True prosperity (falah) comes through taqwa (mindfulness of Allah), not through exploiting others. Avoiding riba and practicing fair dealing leads to blessing in this life and success in the Hereafter. What seems like easy profit through interest actually brings Allah's curse and removes blessing from wealth."
  },
  131: {
    "Guard yourselves against the Fire prepared for the disbelievers": "The believers are warned to protect themselves from Hell. While the Fire is prepared primarily for disbelievers, Muslims who engage in major sins like riba without repentance also risk punishment. This verse serves as motivation to avoid forbidden practices that could lead to the Fire."
  },
  132: {
    "Obey Allah and the Messenger, so you may be shown mercy": "The path to Allah's mercy is through obedience—following Allah's commands as explained by His Messenger ﷺ. This includes all aspects of life: worship, business dealings, social interactions, and personal conduct. Obedience brings mercy; disobedience brings punishment."
  },
  133: {
    "And hasten towards forgiveness from your Lord": "Muslims are commanded to race and rush toward earning Allah's forgiveness. This means quickly repenting from sins, performing good deeds, and seizing every opportunity for righteousness. There should be urgency, not laziness, in seeking Allah's pleasure.",
    "and a Paradise as vast as the heavens and the earth": "Paradise is described as having the width of the heavens and earth combined—an unimaginable expanse. This metaphor emphasizes its vastness and the abundance of its rewards. There is room for everyone who qualifies.",
    "prepared for those mindful ˹of Allah˺": "Paradise has already been prepared—it exists now, waiting for those with taqwa. The people of taqwa are those who are conscious of Allah, who obey His commands, avoid His prohibitions, and live with awareness of His presence."
  },
  134: {
    "˹They are˺ those who donate in prosperity and adversity": "The people of taqwa spend in Allah's cause in all circumstances—when wealthy and when struggling, when times are good and when times are hard. Their generosity is consistent, not dependent on their comfort level.",
    "control their anger": "They suppress and control their rage (kadhm al-ghaydh) rather than acting upon it destructively. When angry, they do not lash out, abuse others, or make rash decisions. This requires immense self-control and is highly praised in Islam. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'The strong person is not the one who overcomes others by his strength, but the one who controls himself while in anger.'",
    "and pardon others": "Beyond controlling anger, they actively forgive those who wrong them. Pardoning (afw) means letting go of the right to retaliate or hold grudges. This is a higher level than mere self-control.",
    "And Allah loves the good-doers": "Those who excel in these qualities are muhsineen—people of ihsan (excellence). Allah loves them, which is the greatest reward anyone could hope for."
  },
  135: {
    "˹They are˺ those who, upon committing an evil deed or wronging themselves, remember Allah": "Even the people of taqwa may slip and commit sins—this is human nature. But their response to sin is immediate: they remember Allah. The awareness of Allah brings them back to their senses.",
    "and seek forgiveness": "After remembering Allah, they ask for His forgiveness. They do not justify their sin, blame others, or pretend it did not happen. They acknowledge their mistake and seek pardon.",
    "and do not knowingly persist in sin": "The key quality is not persisting (israar) in the sin. They do not repeat it deliberately, do not make it a habit, and do not defend it as acceptable. Making a mistake once is human; insisting on it is defiance.",
    "and who forgives sins except Allah?": "This rhetorical question emphasizes that only Allah can forgive sins. No priest, no saint, no human has this authority. This is why we turn directly to Allah for forgiveness."
  },
  136: {
    "Their reward is forgiveness from their Lord": "Those with these qualities will receive what they sought: Allah's forgiveness. Their sins will be erased, and they will meet Allah purified.",
    "and Gardens under which rivers flow, staying there forever": "Their permanent home will be Paradise with flowing rivers—symbols of life, beauty, and abundance. And they will remain there eternally, never to be removed.",
    "How excellent is the reward for those who work ˹righteousness˺": "This is an expression of praise for this reward. What a wonderful compensation for those who strived, who controlled themselves, who repented, and who persevered in righteousness!"
  },
  137: {
    "Similar situations came to pass before you": "History repeats itself. The struggles between truth and falsehood, the tests of believers, the arrogance of disbelievers—all these patterns have occurred before. Muslims should take comfort and learn from this.",
    "so travel throughout the land and see the fate of the deniers": "Allah encourages travel and observation. Visit the ruins of destroyed nations—the people of 'Ad, Thamud, Pharaoh, and others—and see what happened to those who denied the truth. These physical remnants are lessons for those who reflect."
  },
  138: {
    "This is an insight to humanity": "The Quran and its lessons provide clarity (bayan) for all people. The truth is made plain so that no one has an excuse for ignorance.",
    "a guide and a lesson to the God-fearing": "For those with taqwa specifically, the Quran serves as guidance (huda) showing the right path, and as an admonition (maw'idhah) that softens hearts and motivates action. The benefits of the Quran are proportional to one's taqwa."
  },
  139: {
    "Do not falter or grieve": "After the losses at Uhud, believers naturally felt discouraged. Allah commands them not to become weak (wahana) or sad (hazana). These emotions, while natural, should not lead to despair or paralysis.",
    "for you will have the upper hand, if you are ˹true˺ believers": "Despite the setback, the ultimate victory belongs to the believers. The condition is genuine faith (iman). With true faith comes Allah's support, and with His support comes eventual triumph. This promise extends to believers of all times."
  },
  140: {
    "If you have suffered injuries ˹at Uḥud˺, they suffered similarly ˹at Badr˺": "The believers suffered wounds and losses at Uhud. But the disbelievers suffered equally at Badr. Hardship is not proof of Allah's abandonment—both sides experience difficulty.",
    "We alternate these days ˹of victory and defeat˺ among people": "Allah rotates circumstances—sometimes one group succeeds, sometimes another. This is divine wisdom, not randomness. Constant victory could lead to arrogance; occasional setbacks keep people humble and dependent on Allah.",
    "so that Allah may reveal the ˹true˺ believers": "Tests distinguish sincere believers from hypocrites. When things are easy, everyone claims faith. Difficulty reveals who truly believes.",
    "choose martyrs from among you": "Some believers are honored with martyrdom (shahada). This is not punishment but elevation—they are chosen for the highest rank. The martyrs of Uhud were honored by Allah.",
    "and Allah does not like the wrongdoers": "The wrongdoers—those who oppose truth—are not loved by Allah despite any temporary success they may have."
  },
  141: {
    "and distinguish the ˹true˺ believers": "Allah purifies (yumahis) the believers through trials—cleansing them of sins, strengthening their faith, and refining their character. Like gold purified by fire, believers are improved through difficulty.",
    "and destroy the disbelievers": "Ultimately, the disbelievers will be destroyed (yamhaq). Their temporary victories are part of a process that leads to their eventual ruin, either in this world or the next."
  },
  142: {
    "Do you think you will enter Paradise without Allah proving which of you ˹truly˺ struggled ˹for His cause˺": "This rhetorical question challenges any assumption that Paradise comes without effort. Entry into Paradise requires proof of genuine commitment—not just words but actions, not just actions but struggle (jihad) in Allah's cause.",
    "and patiently endured?": "Along with struggle, patience (sabr) is required. True faith is demonstrated through perseverance during hardship, not just enthusiasm during ease. Allah tests to reveal who has these qualities."
  },
  143: {
    "You certainly wished ˹for the opportunity˺ for martyrdom before encountering it": "Before Uhud, some companions had wished they could fight and die as martyrs like those at Badr. They missed Badr and wanted their chance for this honor.",
    "now you have seen it with your own eyes": "At Uhud, they faced the reality of battle—the chaos, the danger, the death. Some who had wished for martyrdom fled when they saw it approaching. This is a reminder that theoretical courage is different from actual courage in the moment of trial."
  },
  144: {
    "Muḥammad is no more than a messenger; other messengers have gone before him": "This crucial verse clarifies the Prophet's ﷺ human nature. He is a messenger—the greatest messenger—but still a human who will die. Previous messengers all died, and their followers continued. The Prophet ﷺ is no exception.",
    "If he were to die or to be killed, would you regress into disbelief?": "At Uhud, a rumor spread that the Prophet ﷺ had been killed. Some believers panicked, and hypocrites used this to spread doubt. This verse asks: is your faith dependent on one person's life? True faith is in Allah, not in any human.",
    "Those who do so will not harm Allah whatsoever": "Anyone who apostasizes because of the Prophet's death harms only themselves. Allah is not affected by human disbelief. His religion will continue regardless.",
    "And Allah will reward those who are grateful": "Those who remain grateful and steadfast—who continue following Islam after the Prophet ﷺ—will be rewarded. Abu Bakr (may Allah be pleased with him) recited this verse after the Prophet's ﷺ actual death, reminding the shocked community that their faith was in Allah."
  },
  145: {
    "No soul can ever die without Allah's Will at the destined time": "Death is entirely in Allah's control. No one dies before their appointed time (ajal), and no one lives beyond it. This should remove fear of battle—if your time has not come, you will not die; if it has, nothing can save you.",
    "Those who desire worldly gain, We will let them have it": "Those who fight or act only for worldly rewards (wealth, status, reputation) may get some of what they seek. But that is all they will receive—nothing in the Hereafter.",
    "and those who desire heavenly reward, We will grant it to them": "Those who seek Allah's pleasure and the reward of the Hereafter will receive it. Their intention determines their reward.",
    "And We will reward those who are grateful": "Gratitude (shukr) leads to reward. Those who thank Allah for His guidance, for the opportunity to struggle in His cause, and for whatever outcome He decrees will be compensated generously."
  },
  146: {
    "˹Imagine˺ how many devotees fought along with their prophets": "Throughout history, many prophets had devoted followers (ribbiyyun—people of deep religious commitment) who fought alongside them for Allah's cause.",
    "and never faltered despite whatever ˹losses˺ they suffered in the cause of Allah": "Despite casualties, injuries, and setbacks, these devoted believers did not weaken (wahanu). They did not lose heart or give up.",
    "nor did they weaken or give in": "They did not become weak (da'ufu) or surrender (istakanu). They remained firm, resilient, and committed to their cause regardless of circumstances.",
    "Allah loves those who persevere": "This is the reward for such steadfastness: Allah's love. Being loved by Allah is the greatest achievement, and it comes to those who patiently persevere through trials."
  },
  147: {
    "And all they said was, \"Our Lord! Forgive our sins and excesses\"": "Their response to hardship was dua (supplication), not complaints. They asked Allah to forgive their sins and their excesses (israf—going beyond bounds). They acknowledged their own shortcomings rather than blaming Allah.",
    "\"make our steps firm\"": "They asked for steadfastness (thabbit aqdamana)—that Allah keep them firm in battle and in faith, not allowing them to flee or waver.",
    "\"and grant us victory over the disbelieving people\"": "Finally, they asked for victory (nasr). Their dua combined humility (seeking forgiveness), dependence on Allah (seeking firmness), and confidence (seeking victory). This is the model dua for believers in difficulty."
  },
  148: {
    "So Allah gave them the reward of this world": "Because of their steadfastness and beautiful supplication, Allah rewarded them in this world—victory, honor, legacy, and good mention throughout history.",
    "and the excellent reward of the Hereafter": "More importantly, they received the best reward of the Hereafter—Paradise and Allah's pleasure. The Hereafter's reward is described as 'excellent' (husn) because it is superior and eternal.",
    "For Allah loves the good-doers": "These people were muhsineen—people of excellence who did more than the minimum, who persevered when others gave up, who turned to Allah when others complained. Allah loves such people."
  },
  149: {
    "O believers! If you yield to the disbelievers, they will drag you back to disbelief": "Obeying the enemies of Islam in matters that contradict faith will lead to apostasy. The disbelievers' goal is to turn Muslims away from Islam, and following their lead accomplishes their objective.",
    "and you will become losers": "Those who abandon faith for disbelief are the ultimate losers—losing this world's blessing, losing the Hereafter's reward, losing everything that truly matters."
  },
  150: {
    "But no! Allah is your Guardian": "Reject the disbelievers' authority—Allah is your true Mawla (guardian, protector, supporter). He alone deserves your obedience and trust.",
    "and He is the best Helper": "Allah is the best of helpers. His support is more powerful and more reliable than any human alliance. Why would believers seek help from Allah's enemies when they have Allah Himself?"
  },
  151: {
    "We will cast horror into the hearts of the disbelievers": "Allah promises to strike fear (ru'b) into the enemies' hearts. This was fulfilled at Uhud when, despite gaining the upper hand, the Quraysh suddenly became fearful and retreated without finishing the battle. The Prophet ﷺ said he was given victory through ru'b cast into enemies' hearts.",
    "for associating ˹false gods˺ with Allah—a practice He has never authorized": "Their terror is a consequence of their shirk. They worship false gods that have no authority from Allah, no power to help them, and no basis in truth.",
    "The Fire will be their home—what an evil place for the wrongdoers to stay": "Their ultimate destination is Hell—an evil residence for those who committed the ultimate wrong of shirk."
  },
  152: {
    "Indeed, Allah fulfilled His promise to you when you ˹initially˺ swept them away by His Will": "At the beginning of Uhud, the Muslims were winning decisively. Allah kept His promise of support, and the disbelievers were being routed.",
    "then your courage weakened and you disputed about the command and disobeyed": "The turning point came when the archers stationed on the hill—commanded by the Prophet ﷺ not to leave their positions under any circumstance—saw the enemy retreating and began to argue. Many left their posts to collect war spoils.",
    "after Allah had brought victory within your reach": "Victory was almost complete. The disobedience occurred after success was assured, making it more tragic. The believers became overconfident and undisciplined.",
    "Some of you were after worldly gain while others desired a heavenly reward": "The Muslim army had mixed motivations. Some prioritized collecting booty (dunya), while others remained focused on Allah's pleasure. This difference in intention affected their actions.",
    "He denied you victory over them as a test, yet He has pardoned you": "Allah allowed the tide to turn as a test and lesson. But He also forgave the believers for their mistake. This combination of discipline and mercy is characteristic of Allah's treatment of sincere believers.",
    "And Allah is Gracious to the believers": "Despite their error, Allah remains gracious to the believers. He corrects, teaches, and forgives—always with their ultimate good in mind."
  },
  153: {
    "˹Remember˺ when you were running far away ˹in panic˺—not looking at anyone": "This describes the chaotic retreat when Khalid ibn al-Walid's cavalry (before his conversion) attacked from behind after the archers left. Muslims fled in confusion, not even looking back at each other.",
    "while the Messenger was calling to you from behind": "The Prophet ﷺ was calling them to return and regroup, but in their panic, many did not respond. This image of the Prophet ﷺ calling while his army fled is deeply moving.",
    "So Allah rewarded your disobedience with distress upon distress": "The consequence of their disobedience was layer upon layer of grief—grief over fleeing, grief over the rumor of the Prophet's death, grief over the martyrs, grief over the setback itself.",
    "Now, do not grieve over the victory you were denied or the injury you suffered": "The purpose of this compounded grief was to teach them that in comparison to these lesser griefs, they should not be devastated by missing victory or suffering injuries. Everything is put in perspective.",
    "And Allah is All-Aware of what you do": "Allah knows all their actions, intentions, and circumstances. His knowledge ensures perfect justice and wisdom in His decrees."
  },
  154: {
    "Then after distress, He sent down serenity in the form of drowsiness overcoming some of you": "After the battle's chaos, Allah sent a calming drowsiness upon the sincere believers—a miraculous peace that allowed them to rest despite the danger. This was a sign of His mercy and acceptance.",
    "while others were disturbed by evil thoughts about Allah—the thoughts of ˹pre-Islamic˺ ignorance": "Another group—the hypocrites—did not receive this peace. Instead, they were consumed by anxiety and began thinking badly of Allah, questioning His wisdom and the Prophet's leadership.",
    "They ask, \"Do we have a say in the matter?\" Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"All matters are destined by Allah.\"": "They questioned whether their opinions mattered in the decision-making. The response is that ultimately all matters belong to Allah—He decrees what He wills.",
    "They conceal in their hearts what they do not reveal to you. They say ˹to themselves˺, \"If we had any say in the matter, none of us would have come to die here.\"": "Secretly, they believed that had they been consulted, they would not have gone to Uhud and suffered losses. This reveals their lack of faith in divine decree.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Even if you were to remain in your homes, those among you who were destined to be killed would have met the same fate.\"": "Death cannot be avoided by staying home. Those destined to die would have found death regardless of their location. This affirms belief in qadr (divine decree).",
    "Through this, Allah tests what is within you and purifies what is in your hearts. And Allah knows best what is ˹hidden˺ in the heart": "The purpose of the trial was to test and purify hearts—revealing true faith versus hypocrisy, strengthening the sincere, and exposing the insincere. Allah knows all that is hidden in hearts."
  },
  155: {
    "Indeed, those ˹believers˺ who fled on the day when the two armies met were made to slip by Satan because of their misdeeds": "Those who retreated at Uhud were caused to stumble by Shaytan, who exploited their previous sins to weaken them in the moment of trial. Past sins have consequences—they can make a person vulnerable to Shaytan's whispers in critical moments.",
    "But Allah has pardoned them": "Despite their fleeing, Allah forgave them. This shows His immense mercy toward sincere believers who made mistakes in moments of weakness.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Forbearing": "Allah is Ghafoor (All-Forgiving)—He covers and erases sins. He is also Haleem (Most Forbearing)—He does not hasten to punish but gives time for repentance. These attributes comfort believers who have made mistakes."
  },
  156: {
    "O believers! Do not be like the unfaithful who say about their brothers who travel throughout the land or engage in battle, \"If they had stayed with us, they would not have died or been killed.\"": "Believers are warned against adopting the mentality of hypocrites and disbelievers who blame travel or fighting for death. They claim that staying home would have prevented death—denying divine decree.",
    "Allah makes such thinking a cause of agony in their hearts": "This false belief actually increases their grief and regret. By thinking death could have been avoided, they torment themselves with 'what ifs' instead of accepting Allah's decree with peace.",
    "It is Allah who gives life and causes death": "Life and death are solely in Allah's hands. No precaution gives life, and no risk causes death except by His will.",
    "And Allah is All-Seeing of what you do": "Allah observes all actions and intentions. Those who trust in Him will be rewarded; those who blame circumstances will continue in their grief."
  },
  157: {
    "Should you be martyred or die in the cause of Allah, then His forgiveness and mercy are far better than whatever ˹wealth˺ those ˹who stay behind˺ accumulate": "Death in Allah's cause—whether in battle or while striving for Islam—brings Allah's forgiveness and mercy. These divine gifts are infinitely more valuable than any worldly wealth the living can accumulate. This should motivate courage and remove fear of death in righteous causes."
  },
  158: {
    "Whether you die or are martyred—all of you will be gathered before Allah": "Regardless of how death occurs, everyone returns to Allah. This universal destination should keep believers focused on preparing for that meeting rather than obsessing over how or when death comes."
  },
  159: {
    "It is out of Allah's mercy that you ˹O Prophet˺ have been lenient with them": "The Prophet's ﷺ gentle character was a mercy from Allah. Despite the serious mistakes made at Uhud—disobedience, fleeing, chaos—he remained soft and understanding with his followers. This gentleness was not weakness but divinely-granted wisdom.",
    "Had you been cruel or hard-hearted, they would have certainly abandoned you": "If the Prophet ﷺ had been harsh, rude, or hard-hearted (qualities some leaders mistakenly think show strength), people would have left him. True leadership attracts through mercy, not fear.",
    "So pardon them, ask Allah's forgiveness for them": "The Prophet ﷺ is instructed to forgive their mistakes and pray for their forgiveness. This models how leaders should treat followers who err—with mercy and intercession, not revenge.",
    "and consult with them in ˹conducting˺ matters": "Despite the failure that partly resulted from consultation before Uhud (where the majority wanted to fight outside Madinah), the Prophet ﷺ is commanded to continue consulting. Consultation (shura) is not abandoned because of one bad outcome—it remains a principle of Islamic governance.",
    "Once you make a decision, put your trust in Allah": "After consultation and careful deliberation, decisive action is required. Once the decision is made, proceed with tawakkul (trust in Allah). Do not second-guess or hesitate—trust that Allah will support righteous efforts.",
    "Surely Allah loves those who trust in Him": "Those who combine proper planning with trust in Allah earn His love. Tawakkul is not passive fatalism—it is active trust that follows proper effort."
  },
  160: {
    "If Allah helps you, none can defeat you": "When Allah grants victory (nasr), no force in the universe can overcome the believers. This was demonstrated at Badr where a small, poorly-equipped force defeated a much larger army.",
    "But if He denies you help, then who else can help you?": "Conversely, if Allah withholds His help, no ally, no strategy, no weapons can provide victory. This was the lesson of Uhud—when believers disobeyed, Allah's help was temporarily withdrawn.",
    "So in Allah let the believers put their trust": "The conclusion is clear: believers must rely completely on Allah. He is the only source of true help and the only guarantor of success."
  },
  161: {
    "It is not appropriate for a prophet to illegally withhold spoils of war": "Some people had accused the Prophet ﷺ of keeping some war spoils for himself—a false accusation. This verse declares that prophets do not commit ghulul (embezzlement from collective wealth). Such dishonesty is beneath their character.",
    "And whoever does so, it will be held against them on the Day of Judgment": "Anyone who steals from war spoils or public funds will carry that stolen item on the Day of Judgment for all to see—a public humiliation. The Prophet ﷺ warned: 'I do not want to see any of you coming on the Day of Judgment carrying a camel, a cow, or sheep on his neck, crying for help and I cannot help him.'",
    "Then every soul will be paid in full for what it has done, and none will be wronged": "Complete justice will be served. Those who were honest will be rewarded; those who stole will be punished. No one will be treated unfairly."
  },
  162: {
    "Are those who seek Allah's pleasure like those who deserve Allah's wrath?": "This rhetorical question emphasizes the vast gulf between two types of people: those who pursue Allah's pleasure through faith and obedience, versus those who earn His anger through disbelief and sin. They are not equal in any way.",
    "Hell is their home. What an evil destination!": "The destination of those who earn Allah's wrath is Hell—the worst possible place. This stark contrast should motivate choosing the path of seeking Allah's pleasure."
  },
  163: {
    "They ˹each˺ have varying degrees in the sight of Allah": "Neither group is uniform. Among those seeking Allah's pleasure, there are varying ranks based on their deeds and sincerity. Similarly, among the wrongdoers, there are varying levels of punishment based on their crimes.",
    "And Allah is All-Seeing of what they do": "Allah sees everything—every action, every intention, every hidden thought. His knowledge ensures that each person receives exactly what they deserve."
  },
  164: {
    "Indeed, Allah has done the believers a ˹great˺ favour by raising a messenger from among them": "Sending Prophet Muhammad ﷺ was a tremendous act of divine favor (minnah). He was not a distant figure but 'from among them'—a human who shared their language, understood their culture, and faced the same challenges they faced. This made his example relatable and followable.",
    "reciting to them His revelations": "The Prophet's ﷺ first mission was to recite Allah's verses (the Quran) to them. Through his recitation, they heard Allah's words directly, receiving guidance for every aspect of life.",
    "purifying them": "Beyond recitation, he purified them (tazkiyah)—cleansing their beliefs from shirk, their morals from corruption, their hearts from diseases like arrogance and envy, and their actions from sins. This purification transformed savage tribes into noble believers.",
    "and teaching them the Book and wisdom": "He taught them the Quran's meanings and the wisdom (hikmah) to apply it properly. Knowledge without wisdom is dangerous; he provided both.",
    "For indeed they had previously been clearly astray": "Before Islam, the Arabs were in clear misguidance—worshipping idols, burying daughters alive, engaging in constant tribal warfare, and living without moral direction. The Prophet ﷺ transformed them completely—a transformation that was clearly miraculous and a proof of Allah's favor."
  },
  165: {
    "Why is it when you suffered casualties ˹at Uḥud˺—although you had made your enemy suffer twice as much ˹at Badr˺—you protested, \"How could this be?\"": "The Muslims lost about 70 martyrs at Uhud, while at Badr they had killed about 70 disbelievers and captured another 70. When they faced this setback, some wondered how this could happen to believers fighting for Allah's cause. The question reflects a misunderstanding—they assumed victory was guaranteed regardless of their actions.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"It is because of your disobedience.\"": "The Prophet ﷺ is instructed to give the clear answer: the defeat came from their own mistakes. The archers disobeyed orders, some prioritized worldly gains over discipline, and this led to the reversal. Allah's help is conditional on obedience.",
    "Surely Allah is Most Capable of everything": "Allah could have granted victory despite their mistakes—He has power over all things. But He chose to teach them a lesson through consequences. His allowing defeat was also a manifestation of His wisdom and power."
  },
  166: {
    "So what you suffered on the day the two armies met was by Allah's Will": "Nothing happens without Allah's permission. The setback at Uhud was not outside Allah's knowledge or control—He permitted it for specific purposes.",
    "so that He might distinguish the ˹true˺ believers": "One purpose was to identify who truly believed. In times of ease, everyone appears faithful. Hardship reveals who genuinely trusts Allah and who was only along for success."
  },
  167: {
    "and expose the hypocrites": "The second purpose was to expose the hypocrites. Abdullah ibn Ubayy withdrew with 300 men before the battle—nearly one-third of the Muslim army—claiming the Muslims were going to get killed needlessly.",
    "When it was said to them, \"Come fight in the cause of Allah or ˹at least˺ defend yourselves,\" they replied, \"If we had known there was fighting, we would have definitely gone with you.\"": "When urged to either fight for Allah or at minimum defend their homes and families, they made excuses. They pretended there would be no real battle, making a false excuse to justify their desertion. Their claim was absurd—they were marching to meet an invading army.",
    "They were closer to disbelief than to belief on that day—for saying with their mouths what was not in their hearts": "Their actions revealed their true state: they were nearer to kufr (disbelief) than iman (faith). Their words contradicted their hearts—the definition of hypocrisy.",
    "Allah is All-Knowing of what they hide": "Though hypocrites may fool people, Allah knows exactly what is in their hearts. Their hidden intentions are fully exposed to Him."
  },
  168: {
    "Those who sat at home, saying about their brothers, \"Had they listened to us, they would not have been killed.\"": "After the battle, the hypocrites claimed credit for their 'wisdom' in staying behind. They blamed the martyrs for not listening to them, implying that obedience to their advice would have prevented death.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Try not to die if what you say is true!\"": "This is a powerful challenge: if they truly have the ability to avoid death through caution, let them prevent their own death forever. Of course, they cannot—death comes to everyone regardless of precautions. Their claim that staying home prevents death is false. The martyrs gained honor; the hypocrites gained nothing but shame."
  },
  169: {
    "Never think of those martyred in the cause of Allah as dead": "This is a direct command not to consider martyrs dead in the ordinary sense. While their bodies may be buried, their reality is different from other deceased people.",
    "In fact, they are alive with their Lord, well provided for": "The martyrs are alive in a special way—their souls are with Allah, enjoying provisions in Paradise. According to authentic hadith, the souls of martyrs are in green birds that roam Paradise, eating its fruits and drinking from its rivers, and returning to lamps hanging from Allah's Throne. They are conscious, joyful, and blessed."
  },
  170: {
    "rejoicing in Allah's bounties": "The martyrs are in a state of joy (fariheen)—celebrating what Allah has given them from His grace. Death did not bring them sorrow but immense happiness.",
    "and being delighted for those yet to join them": "They are also happy for their believing brothers and sisters still alive who are on the same path. They look forward to their companions joining them in Paradise.",
    "There will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve": "They have no fear about the future and no grief about the past. All anxiety is removed. This is the perfect peace that believers seek."
  },
  171: {
    "They are joyful for receiving Allah's grace and bounty": "Their joy is specifically for the blessings (ni'mah) and extra favor (fadl) from Allah. They recognize that what they received far exceeds what they sacrificed.",
    "and that Allah does not deny the reward of the believers": "They rejoice in knowing that Allah fulfills His promise—He does not waste or lose the reward of any believer. This certainty adds to their happiness. Their sacrifice was not in vain; every effort was recorded and rewarded."
  },
  172: {
    "˹As for˺ those who responded to the call of Allah and His Messenger after their injury": "After Uhud, despite being wounded and exhausted, the Prophet ﷺ called the believers to pursue the retreating enemy to Hamra al-Asad (about 8 miles from Madinah). This was to show that the Muslims were not defeated and to deter the Quraysh from returning. The believers responded despite their injuries.",
    "those of them who did good and were mindful ˹of Allah˺ will have a great reward": "Those who combined good deeds (ihsan) with God-consciousness (taqwa) in this response will receive a tremendous reward. Their willingness to sacrifice again, immediately after suffering, demonstrated exceptional faith."
  },
  173: {
    "Those who were warned, \"Your enemies have mobilized their forces against you, so fear them\"": "On the way to Hamra al-Asad, people tried to frighten them with reports that the Quraysh had regrouped and were coming back with a larger force. This psychological warfare was meant to demoralize them.",
    "the warning only made them grow stronger in faith": "Instead of becoming afraid, their faith increased. True believers are strengthened by challenges, not weakened. The threat made them rely more on Allah.",
    "and they replied, \"Allah ˹alone˺ is sufficient ˹as an aid˺ for us and ˹He˺ is the best Protector\"": "They responded with the powerful phrase: 'Hasbunallahu wa ni'mal wakeel' (Allah is sufficient for us, and He is the best Disposer of affairs). This is the same phrase Ibrahim said when thrown into the fire. It expresses complete trust in Allah regardless of circumstances."
  },
  174: {
    "So they returned with Allah's favours and grace, suffering no harm": "They came back safely with blessings from Allah—no battle occurred because the Quraysh, hearing the Muslims were pursuing them, fled quickly to Makkah. The believers' courage was rewarded with safety and honor.",
    "For they sought to please Allah": "Their motivation was purely to seek Allah's pleasure (ridwan), not worldly gain or reputation. This sincere intention brought divine protection.",
    "And surely Allah is ˹the˺ Lord of infinite bounty": "Allah's favor is vast and unlimited. He rewards those who trust Him generously—often in ways they did not expect."
  },
  175: {
    "That ˹warning˺ was only ˹from˺ Satan, trying to prompt you to fear his followers": "The scary reports about enemy forces were Shaytan's psychological tactics. He tries to make believers fear his allies (disbelievers and hypocrites) to prevent them from doing good.",
    "So do not fear them; fear Me if you are ˹true˺ believers": "The command is clear: do not fear Shaytan's allies. Fear only Allah. True faith means fearing Allah alone, which liberates one from all other fears. When you fear Allah, you fear nothing else."
  },
  176: {
    "˹O Prophet!˺ Do not grieve for those who race to disbelieve": "The Prophet ﷺ felt sad when people rejected faith or when hypocrites betrayed the community. Allah comforts him: do not let their behavior sadden you.",
    "surely they will not harm Allah in the least": "Their disbelief and hostility cannot hurt Allah. They only harm themselves. Allah's religion will prevail regardless of opposition.",
    "It is Allah's Will to disallow them a share in the Hereafter": "Allah intends that they have no portion of Paradise. Because of their choices, they have forfeited the Hereafter.",
    "and they will suffer a tremendous punishment": "Beyond losing Paradise, they will face severe punishment. Their rushing toward disbelief leads to devastating consequences."
  },
  177: {
    "Those who trade belief for disbelief will never harm Allah in the least": "Some people had faith and then abandoned it for disbelief—the worst trade possible. They exchanged eternal success for eternal failure. But this harms only themselves, not Allah.",
    "and they will suffer a painful punishment": "Their punishment is described as 'aleem' (painful, agonizing). The pain is proportional to what they knowingly rejected."
  },
  178: {
    "Those who disbelieve should not think that living longer is good for them": "Disbelievers sometimes take their long lives and continued prosperity as signs of Allah's approval. They assume more time means more success. This is a dangerous delusion.",
    "They are only given more time to increase in sin": "The extension of their lives is actually to allow them to accumulate more sins. More time means more wrongdoing, which means worse punishment.",
    "and they will suffer a humiliating punishment": "Their punishment will be 'muheen' (humiliating, disgraceful). The pride they had in their worldly success will be replaced by utter humiliation."
  },
  179: {
    "Allah would not leave the believers in the condition you were in, until He distinguished the good from the evil ˹among you˺": "Allah does not leave believers in a state where hypocrites are mixed among them without distinction. Through trials like Uhud, the pure (tayyib) are separated from the corrupt (khabith). Tests reveal true character.",
    "Nor would Allah ˹directly˺ reveal to you the unseen": "Allah does not give ordinary people direct knowledge of the unseen—including who is sincere and who is hypocritical. We cannot read hearts.",
    "but He chooses whoever He wills as a messenger": "Knowledge of the unseen is given only to prophets as Allah chooses. The Prophet ﷺ received revelation about some hypocrites, but even he did not know all hidden matters.",
    "So believe in Allah and His messengers": "The command is to have faith in Allah and accept His messengers. Following the Prophet ﷺ is the path to guidance.",
    "And if you are faithful and mindful ˹of Allah˺, you will receive a great reward": "The combination of faith (iman) and God-consciousness (taqwa) leads to tremendous reward. This is the formula for success."
  },
  180: {
    "And do not let those who ˹greedily˺ withhold Allah's bounties think it is good for them—in fact, it is bad for them!": "Those who are stingy with the wealth Allah gave them, refusing to pay zakah or spend in His cause, should not imagine this hoarding benefits them. It actually harms them—spiritually now and physically on the Day of Judgment.",
    "They will be leashed ˹by their necks˺ on the Day of Judgment with whatever ˹wealth˺ they used to withhold": "The Prophet ﷺ explained that the wealth they hoarded will be transformed into a snake that will be wrapped around their necks, biting them and saying: 'I am your wealth, I am your treasure.' What they clung to becomes their torment.",
    "And Allah is the ˹sole˺ inheritor of the heavens and the earth": "Ultimately, all wealth returns to Allah. Everyone dies and leaves their possessions behind. Allah inherits everything—so why cling to what you cannot keep?",
    "And Allah is All-Aware of what you do": "Allah knows exactly how much each person has and how much they give or withhold. Nothing is hidden from His accounting."
  },
  181: {
    "Indeed, Allah has heard those ˹among the Jews˺ who said, \"Allah is poor; we are rich!\"": "When the verse commanding charity was revealed (saying Allah would give a 'goodly loan' to those who spend), some Jews mocked it, saying: 'If Allah needs to borrow from us, He must be poor and we are rich!' This was deliberate blasphemy.",
    "We have certainly recorded their slurs and their killing of prophets unjustly": "Allah records every statement—especially blasphemous ones. He also records their historical crimes, including murdering prophets. These records will be evidence against them.",
    "Then We will say, \"Taste the torment of burning!\"": "On the Day of Judgment, they will be told to taste the burning fire. The word 'taste' (dhooqu) implies experiencing something directly and intensely."
  },
  182: {
    "This is ˹the reward˺ for what your hands have done": "Their punishment is a direct result of their own actions—their blasphemy, their rejection of prophets, their mockery of divine revelation.",
    "And Allah is never unjust to ˹His˺ creation": "Allah does not wrong anyone. Every punishment is deserved and proportional. If they suffer, it is because of what they earned. Allah is perfectly just."
  },
  183: {
    "Those ˹are the same people˺ who say, \"Allah has commanded us not to believe in any messenger unless he brings us an offering to be consumed by fire ˹from the sky˺.\"": "Some Jews demanded a specific miracle as proof of prophethood: an offering that would be consumed by heavenly fire (as happened with some previous prophets). They claimed this was required by Allah before they would believe.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Other prophets did in fact come to you before me with clear proofs and ˹even˺ what you demanded—why then did you kill them, if what you say is true?\"": "The Prophet ﷺ is told to challenge their sincerity: previous prophets came with both clear signs and the very miracle they demanded, yet their ancestors rejected and killed those prophets. If the miracle was truly their criterion, why did they not believe then? This exposes their excuse as insincere."
  },
  184: {
    "If you are rejected by them, so too were messengers before you who came with clear proofs, divine Books, and enlightening Scriptures": "This is consolation for the Prophet ﷺ: rejection is not unique to you. Previous messengers also faced denial despite bringing: (1) clear proofs (bayyinat—miracles and evidence), (2) divine scriptures (zubur—books of wisdom and guidance), and (3) enlightening scriptures (kitab muneer—illuminating revelations). If they rejected messengers with all of this, their rejection of you is no surprise. You are in noble company."
  },
  185: {
    "Every soul will taste death": "This is an absolute, universal truth. No one—rich or poor, powerful or weak, believer or disbeliever—escapes death. Every person will 'taste' it, meaning experience it directly and personally.",
    "And you will only receive your full reward on the Day of Judgment": "Complete recompense—whether reward or punishment—comes only on the Day of Judgment. This world does not settle all accounts; the Hereafter does.",
    "Whoever is spared from the Fire and is admitted into Paradise will ˹indeed˺ triumph": "True success (fawz) is defined here: being saved from Hell and entering Paradise. Everything else people call 'success'—wealth, fame, power—is secondary. This is the ultimate victory.",
    "whereas the life of this world is no more than the delusion of enjoyment": "Worldly life is 'mata' al-ghuroor'—deceptive enjoyment. It appears valuable but is ultimately an illusion that deceives people about what truly matters. Those who prioritize dunya over akhirah are fooled by this deception."
  },
  186: {
    "You ˹believers˺ will surely be tested in your wealth and yourselves": "Allah guarantees that believers will face trials. These tests will affect their wealth (through loss, poverty, obligations like zakah, or sacrifice) and their selves (through illness, injury, death of loved ones, personal struggles). This is not a possibility but a certainty.",
    "and you will certainly hear many hurtful words from those who were given the Scripture before you and ˹from˺ the polytheists": "Beyond material tests, believers will face verbal abuse—mockery, insults, lies, and propaganda—from both the People of the Book and polytheists. This psychological warfare is part of the test.",
    "But if you are patient and mindful ˹of Allah˺—surely this is a resolve to aspire to": "The prescription for these trials is sabr (patience) and taqwa (God-consciousness). Maintaining both through difficulties is described as 'azm al-umoor'—the most resolute and praiseworthy course of action. This combination is what Allah asks of believers, and He promises great reward for those who maintain it."
  },
  187: {
    "˹Remember, O Prophet,˺ when Allah took the covenant of those who were given the Scripture to make it known to people and not hide it": "Allah made a solemn covenant with the People of the Book—the scholars of the Torah and Gospel—to explain scripture clearly to people and never conceal its truths. This included the prophecies about Prophet Muhammad ﷺ and the core teachings of monotheism. Knowledge of divine revelation is a trust that carries serious responsibility.",
    "yet they cast it behind their backs": "They threw this sacred covenant behind their backs—a metaphor for complete disregard and abandonment. Instead of fulfilling their obligation, they actively violated it by concealing portions of scripture that contradicted their interests.",
    "and traded it for a fleeting gain": "They sold their covenant with Allah for 'thaman qaleel'—a small, worthless price. This refers to worldly benefits: maintaining their religious authority, receiving gifts from followers, avoiding conflict with powerful people, or preserving their status. They exchanged eternal reward for temporary, trivial gains.",
    "What a miserable profit!": "This is divine commentary on their transaction: what a terrible trade they made! They gained nothing of value and lost everything that mattered. This warning applies to anyone—especially scholars and religious leaders—who conceals truth for worldly benefit."
  },
  188: {
    "Do not let those who rejoice in their misdeeds": "Some people take pride and pleasure in their wrongdoing—they are happy about their deception, their concealment of truth, their manipulation of religion for personal gain. This perverse joy compounds their sin.",
    "and love to take credit for what they have not done": "They desire to be praised for virtues they do not possess. For example, the Jewish scholars wanted credit for being guides to truth while they concealed it, or wanted praise for following God while they disobeyed Him. This applies to anyone who seeks undeserved recognition—pretending to be pious, knowledgeable, or charitable when they are not.",
    "think they will escape torment": "Such people should not imagine they will avoid punishment. Their self-deception and public deception will not save them from accountability.",
    "They will suffer a painful punishment": "Their punishment will be severe (aleem—painful and agonizing). The combination of wrongdoing, rejoicing in it, and seeking false praise deserves serious consequences."
  },
  189: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth": "Complete sovereignty and ownership belong exclusively to Allah. He is the Malik (King/Owner) of everything that exists. This includes authority, control, and possession of all creation. No one shares this kingdom with Him.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable of everything": "His ownership is backed by unlimited power (qadeer). He can do anything He wills—create, destroy, give life, cause death, reward, punish. Nothing is beyond His capability. This combination of ownership and power means absolute sovereignty."
  },
  190: {
    "Indeed, in the creation of the heavens and the earth": "The very existence and intricate design of the heavens (the universe beyond earth) and the earth itself are signs (ayat) pointing to the Creator. The vastness of space, the complexity of ecosystems, the precision of natural laws—all testify to intelligent design.",
    "and the alternation of the day and night": "The regular cycle of day and night—the rotation of the earth, the perfect distance from the sun, the consistency of this pattern—is another sign. It provides the rhythm for life, agriculture, work, and rest. This alternation is so precise it can be predicted centuries in advance.",
    "there are signs for people of reason": "These signs are recognized by 'ulil albab'—people of understanding, intellect, and insight. They use their minds to reflect on creation and conclude there must be a wise, powerful Creator. These are people who think deeply rather than accepting things superficially."
  },
  191: {
    "˹They are˺ those who remember Allah while standing, sitting, and lying on their sides": "The people of understanding remember Allah (dhikr) in all positions and at all times—whether standing, sitting, or lying down. This means their remembrance is constant, not limited to formal prayer times. They maintain awareness of Allah during all activities and circumstances, whether healthy or sick, active or resting.",
    "and reflect on the creation of the heavens and the earth": "Beyond remembrance, they engage in tafakkur (deep reflection) on the creation around them. They observe nature, contemplate the universe, and think about the wisdom behind creation. This intellectual engagement with creation leads to greater faith.",
    "˹and pray˺, \"Our Lord! You have not created ˹all of˺ this without purpose\"": "Their reflection leads to a profound conclusion: this vast, complex creation is not 'batil' (purposeless, vain, or absurd). Everything has meaning, wisdom, and purpose. The universe is not random but designed with intention. This realization increases their awe of Allah.",
    "Glory be to You!": "They declare Allah's perfection (subhanaka)—He is far above any imperfection, any comparison to creation, any limitation. This is tasbih, glorifying Allah by affirming His transcendence.",
    "Protect us from the torment of the Fire": "After affirming Allah's perfection and purpose in creation, they make a humble request: save us from Hell. Despite their righteousness, they remain humble and fearful, never taking salvation for granted."
  },
  192: {
    "Our Lord! Indeed, those You commit to the Fire will be ˹completely˺ disgraced!": "They continue their supplication by acknowledging that whoever enters Hell has been utterly humiliated (akhzayta). The disgrace is complete—physical, psychological, and spiritual. This recognition motivates them to seek protection from such a fate.",
    "And the wrongdoers will have no helpers": "Those who wronged themselves through disbelief and sin will have no one to help them escape punishment. No friends, no intercessors, no protectors—they will be completely abandoned. This realization increases their urgency in seeking Allah's protection."
  },
  193: {
    "Our Lord! We have heard the caller to ˹true˺ belief, ˹proclaiming,˺ 'Believe in your Lord ˹alone˺,' so we believed": "They describe their journey to faith. They heard the 'caller' (munadi)—the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ, or the Quran, or the call of Islam—inviting them to believe in their Lord alone. They responded positively to this call and embraced faith. This shows the importance of proclaiming truth and the beauty of responding to it.",
    "Our Lord! Forgive our sins": "Despite their faith and righteousness, they ask for forgiveness of their sins (dhunub). They acknowledge that even believers sin and need Allah's forgiveness.",
    "absolve us of our misdeeds": "They also ask that their bad deeds (sayyi'at) be erased or covered. There is a subtle difference: forgiveness removes punishment, while covering/absolution (takfeer) removes the stain and record of the sin entirely.",
    "and allow us ˹each˺ to die as one of the virtuous": "Their final request is to die among the abrar (the righteous, the virtuous). They want to maintain their faith until death and be counted among the good people in the Hereafter. Death in a state of righteousness is the ultimate success."
  },
  194: {
    "Our Lord! Grant us what You have promised us through Your messengers": "They ask Allah to fulfill the promises He made through His messengers—particularly the promise of Paradise for believers, victory for truth, and reward for good deeds. They are asking based on Allah's own promise, not on their own merit.",
    "and do not put us to shame on Judgment Day": "They ask not to be humiliated (tukhzina) on the Day of Resurrection. They want to be among those honored, not disgraced.",
    "for certainly You never fail in Your promise": "They conclude by affirming their certainty in Allah's trustworthiness. Allah never breaks His promise (la tukhlifu al-mi'ad). This statement combines a reminder to themselves of Allah's reliability with confidence in receiving what they asked for. It also shows proper adab in dua—ending with praise and affirmation of Allah's attributes."
  },
  195: {
    "So their Lord responded to them": "Allah directly answered their beautiful supplications. This shows that sincere, heartfelt prayers do not go unheard. Allah responds to those who call upon Him with sincerity.",
    "\"I will never deny any of you—male or female—the reward of your deeds\"": "Allah guarantees that no good deed will be lost or unrewarded—whether performed by men or women. This was revealed partly because some women asked whether they would receive equal reward despite not being able to participate in certain physical battles. Allah confirms complete equality in spiritual reward based on deeds.",
    "Both are equal in reward": "Men and women come from one another (in origin, in support, in community) and are equal in their potential for reward. Gender does not diminish the value of righteous deeds.",
    "Those who migrated or were expelled from their homes": "Those who made hijrah (migration for Allah's sake), whether voluntarily leaving for faith or being forcibly expelled by enemies, are specifically mentioned for honor.",
    "and were persecuted for My sake": "Those who suffered harm, torture, or difficulty specifically because of their commitment to Allah receive special recognition.",
    "and fought and ˹some˺ were martyred": "Those who fought in Allah's cause (jihad) and those who were killed as martyrs receive the highest honor.",
    "I will certainly forgive their sins": "Allah promises to erase all their sins—a complete cleansing of their record. The sacrifices they made for His sake warrant this comprehensive forgiveness.",
    "and admit them into Gardens under which rivers flow": "Their eternal home will be Paradise with flowing rivers—the ultimate reward and comfort after their struggles.",
    "as a reward from Allah": "This is not something they earned independently—it is a gift and reward (thawab) from Allah. While their deeds are the cause, Allah's generosity is the source.",
    "And with Allah is the finest reward": "Whatever Allah has is better than anything in this world. His rewards are supreme (husn al-thawab)—the best possible compensation."
  },
  196: {
    "Do not be deceived by the prosperity of the disbelievers throughout the land": "Believers should not be fooled (taghurra) by seeing disbelievers moving freely, conducting business successfully, enjoying wealth and power, and appearing to prosper. This worldly success is not a sign of Allah's approval or their correctness. Sometimes Allah gives worldly success to disbelievers as a test, or to allow them to increase in sin, or simply because He has reserved their recompense for the Hereafter."
  },
  197: {
    "It is only a brief enjoyment": "Their prosperity is 'mata qaleel'—a small, temporary enjoyment. Compared to eternity, even a lifetime of luxury is nothing. Like a traveler's provisions that run out, their worldly gains will end.",
    "Then Hell will be their home—what an evil place to rest": "After their brief pleasure, their permanent destination is Hellfire. The word 'mihad' (place to rest/bed) is used sarcastically—Hell is the worst possible resting place. They exchanged eternal comfort for temporary pleasure."
  },
  198: {
    "But those who are mindful of their Lord will be in Gardens under which rivers flow": "In contrast to disbelievers' temporary pleasure, the people of taqwa (those mindful of Allah) will have Paradise—with flowing rivers symbolizing life, beauty, and abundance.",
    "to stay there forever": "Their reward is 'khalideen' (eternal, everlasting). Unlike worldly enjoyment that ends, Paradise never ends. The pleasure never diminishes, never gets boring, never fades.",
    "as an accommodation from Allah": "This is described as 'nuzul' (hospitality, welcoming accommodation)—like a generous host preparing the finest accommodations for honored guests. Allah Himself is their Host.",
    "And what is with Allah is best for the virtuous": "Everything Allah has prepared for the abrar (the righteous, the virtuous) is superior to anything in this world. The Prophet ﷺ said: 'A place in Paradise as small as a whip is better than the world and everything in it.' This should motivate choosing the lasting over the temporary."
  },
  199: {
    "Indeed, there are some among the People of the Book who truly believe in Allah": "The Quran acknowledges that not all People of the Book are the same. Some genuinely believe in Allah—not just verbally, but with true faith in their hearts.",
    "and what has been revealed to you ˹believers˺": "They believe in the Quran revealed to Muslims. When they encounter Islam and recognize it as truth, they accept it rather than rejecting it out of pride or tribal loyalty.",
    "and what was revealed to them": "They also maintain belief in the original revelations given to their own prophets—the Torah and Gospel. They do not reject their own heritage but see continuity between all divine revelations.",
    "They humble themselves before Allah": "They are 'khashi'een'—humble, submissive, deeply reverent before Allah. There is no arrogance, no pride, no sense of superiority. They approach Allah with the proper attitude of servitude.",
    "never trading Allah's revelations for a fleeting gain": "Unlike those condemned earlier, these believers do not sell Allah's signs for worldly profit. They do not conceal truth for money, status, or convenience. Their integrity remains intact.",
    "Their reward is with their Lord": "Such people will be rewarded by Allah. This includes figures like the Negus (Christian king of Abyssinia who accepted Islam), and the scholars who recognized Muhammad ﷺ and believed in him, like Abdullah ibn Salam.",
    "Surely Allah is swift in reckoning": "Allah quickly accounts for deeds. He does not delay in recording actions or in bringing recompense. Those who believe from among the People of the Book will receive their reward without delay."
  },
  200: {
    "O believers! Patiently endure": "The first command is to have sabr (patience, perseverance, endurance). This includes patience in obeying Allah's commands, patience in avoiding sins, and patience when facing difficulties and trials. Sabr is the foundation of success.",
    "persevere": "Saabiru (from the same root as sabr) means to persistently practice patience—to compete with others in patience, to outlast your enemies in endurance, to maintain patience even when it becomes difficult. It suggests steadfastness in the face of prolonged challenges.",
    "stand on guard": "Rabitu means to be stationed, vigilant, and ready. Originally it referred to tying horses at the frontier, ready for battle—a state of constant readiness to defend Islam. Spiritually, it means guarding one's faith, being alert to spiritual dangers, maintaining the boundaries Allah has set, and being prepared for any challenge to Islam.",
    "and be mindful of Allah": "Ittaqu Allah—have taqwa, be conscious of Allah in all circumstances. Let awareness of Allah guide your decisions, restrain you from wrong, and motivate you toward good. Taqwa is the umbrella that contains all other virtues.",
    "so you may be successful": "La'allakum tuflihun—so that you may achieve true success (falah). These four qualities—patience, persistent patience, vigilance, and God-consciousness—are the formula for success in this life and the Hereafter. This is how believers triumph over challenges, how the Muslim community remains strong, and how individuals achieve their ultimate purpose."
  }
};